[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B10"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41961351"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann. Black prepares ...d5 next and makes sure that the pawn is protected, so exd5 can be answered by cxd5. This is the simple idea behind this big opening! But from now on things are far from simple. The positionally sound concept of c6+d5 is that a clear route is opened for the light-squared bishop on c8. This problem piece can go to g4, f5 or even sometimes to e6.

While Black is busy with the execution of this plan, White has almost a free hand to choose between a lot of very different set-ups. This course is organized in three major parts that are equally important. } 
2. d4 ( 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 { The Classical variation is the first part of the course. This used to be the big mainline. The opinion was that White was slightly better with more space and easy development - a judgement the modern } 4...Nf6 5.Nxf6+ exf6! { questions. } ) ( 2.d4 d5 3.e5 { The Advance variation is White's most popular choice these days. The extra space can be a big asset. I propose we meet it with the dynamic } 3...c5 { with good counterplay. This is the second part. } ) ( 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.Bd3 { , The Exchange variation, and the Panov } { 4.c4 are covered in the final part of the course, together with all other deviations on move 2 and 3. } ) *

