[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42720293"]

1. e4 c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 { White simply protects the e-pawn. } dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { This is the modern dynamic move. } 
5. Ng3 { We will start by looking at some of White's more random tries. Firstly, White is not forced to take on f6! Moving the knight away from e4 is illogical: it loses time and refrains from inflicting some structural damage on Black's position. Yet it avoids mainline theory and that is a benefit in itself for some players. } h5! {[%cal Gh5h4][%csl Gg3]} ( { The knight is not that good on g3 and Black immediately prepares to attack it with the h-pawn. A decent alternative is } 5...g6 { followed by ...Bg7 and ...O-O. } ) 
6. h4 { White decides to stop the pawn march. } c5! ( { Actually, } 6...Bg4 { is the most common move. The straight attack on the centre with } ) ( 6...c5 { gives Black active play at once, though. } ) 
7. dxc5 Qxd1+ ( { Also possible is } 7...Qa5+ 8.c3 Qxc5 { , but I wouldn't be surprised if White is somewhat better there. } ) 
8. Kxd1 e6 {[%csl Gc5]} { Black is ready to recapture the pawn with ...Bxc5 with a superb position. White has to cling to the extra pawn with all means not to be worse. } ( { The slightly more active } 8...e5 { is also fine, for instance } 9.b4 a5 10.c3 Nc6 11.Bd2 Bg4+ 12.Kc1 Be7 { with good compensation for the pawn. It's a matter of taste whether to play 8...e6 or 8...e5. } ) 
9. b4 a5 
10. c3 Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} { Black will castle next. There is excellent long-term compensation for the pawn. White's position is rather stiff and Black can improve with moves like ...Rd8 and ...Nd5. } 
*

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classical 6.Nf3"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42720294"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 { White simply protects the e-pawn. } dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6! { This is the modern dynamic move. } 
5. Nxf6+ exf6! {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Retaking on f6 with } 5...exf6 { looks suspicious. Why give White a nice pawn majority on the queenside almost for free? Practice has shown that it is not so easy for White to exploit this positional advantage, and you can add that although it doesn't seem like much, Black's extra pawn on the kingside gives good protection for the king. The real benefit of ...exf6 is that the black pieces have access to good squares, and it will be easy to get castled. } ) 
6. Nf3 { This has been played a lot. Not so surprisingly perhaps, since it is an obvious move. In my opinion, the popularity is not justified if we go a little deeper. On f3 the knight is not at all well-placed. The black doubled pawn, more specifically the f6-pawn, controls both g5 and e5 and White's own pawn on d4 takes another square away. If you add all this up, then it is clear that the knight on f3 doesn't have much potential - it just stands there. Of course, in the opening much is about getting the pieces out and the knight move fulfills that obligation. Next, the bishop can go to e2... But that is also a passive piece then.

Long story short: The knight is better on e2 than f3. Then it can go to g3 and perhaps even jump to the juicy f5-square, and from e2 it also helps to play Bf4 and contest Black's strong Bd6. } ( { That is why } 6.c3 { followed by Bd3 and Ne2 is the best white set-up. See more about that in the 6.c3 chapter [/course/261638/6]! } ) Bd6 
7. Bd3 { The natural set-up. } O-O 
8. O-O Bg4! {[%cal Gg4d1]} { Exploiting that White didn't play h3. The pin is quite annoying. Of course, Black could also play } { 9...Re8 followed by ...Nd7 and ...Nf8 with a normal position. } 
9. h3 { It makes sense to ask the bishop what it wants. } Bh5 
10. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e8]} { White takes the e-file before Black can play Re8. } Re8 ( { Simple and good. } 10...Nd7 { is also fine. } ) 
11. Rxe8+ Qxe8 
12. Be3 Nd7 { Black's moves come very easy. } 
13. c4 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d1]} { All black pieces are working. } 
14. Qe2 $146  ( { Or } 14.Be2 f5! { , planning ...Nf6 with good play as in a couple of email games. } ) Nf8 
15. Rd1 Ne6 { Black has good pieces. The position is balanced. } 
*

