1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 { White simply protects the e-pawn. } dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { This is the modern dynamic move. } 
5. Nxf6+ exf6 ( { Retaking on f6 with } 5...exf6 { looks suspicious. Why give White a nice pawn majority on the queenside almost for free? Practice has shown that it is not so easy for White to exploit this positional advantage, and you can add that although it doesn't seem like much, Black's extra pawn on the kingside gives good protection for the king. The real benefit of ...exf6 is that the black pieces have access to good squares, and it will be easy to get castled. } ) 
6. c3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2][%csl Gc3,Gd4]} { The big mainline. White strengthens the centre and prepares the optimal set-up with Bd3 and Ne2. } Bd6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. Bd3 O-O 
8. Qc2 {[%csl Gh7]} { This used to be played almost automatically. The attack on h7 forces Black to weaken the kingside somewhat, after which White will castle long and try to exploit the newly created weakness on the kingside to open lines and get a strong attack. } Re8+ { A good intermediate check. } 
9. Ne2 h6!? { This old move is totally underestimated! I rediscovered it in Alex Banzea's course The Caro-Kann: Simplified. Of course, it is a well-known move. Nobody took it serious, because it really is a weakening of Black's position. White has two ways to exploit it: castle long and use the h6-pawn as a hook to open lines, or castle short and use the nice f5-square since Black won't be able to guard it with ...g6 anymore because that would lose the h6-pawn. } ( { The modern solution for Black is } 9...h5!? { . This spectacular new move made fighting players return to the Caro-Kann, and of course it was the subject of my book Playing the Caro-Kann. The move } ) ( 9...h5!? { was hot at that time, and a very fine example of when the avant-garde meets the mainstream. It has been analyzed and played a lot since then, and there is just so much theory.

An excessive amount of opening theory in general is the curse of modern chess. It is like a line from David Bowie's apocalyptic song Five Years: 'My brain hurts like a warehouse, it had no room to spare, I had to cram so many things to store everything in there'. This is a perfect description of the mental state of a chess professional! } ) ( { I started analyzing the } 9...h6 { move very deeply and came to a surprising conclusion: it is just as good as } ) ( 9...h5 { objectively speaking, but much simpler to handle and therefore a great practical choice. Furthermore, at least for now, it has a big surprise value. } ) 
10. O-O! ( { If White wants to castle short it is optimal to do it at once. Various move orders like } 10.Be3 Nd7 11.O-O { or @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3pp1/2pb1p1p/8/3P4/2PB4/PPQ1NPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10.h3 Nd7 11.O-O or @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3pp1/2pb1p1p/8/3P4/2PB4/PPQ1NPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10.Bd2 Nd7 11.O-O will inevitably lead to the same positions that arise after 10.O-O. } ) Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f8]} { The knight is on the way to f8. } 
11. Bf4 {[%csl Gd6]} { Exchanging Black's strong bishop is a good strategy. } Nf8 ( { Beware, White's last move wasn't a blunder! The small combination } 11...Rxe2 12.Qxe2 Bxf4 { nets some material, but after } 13.Qe4 { it is all over for Black! } 13...Bd6 14.Qh7+ Kf8 15.Rae1 { and White wins. } ) 
12. Bxd6 ( 12.Bg3 Bg4 { is fine for Black. } ) Qxd6 { You would think that White is slightly better: a superior pawn structure, good pieces, extra space. However, it is surprisingly difficult to turn this into an advantage, and Black's position has more potential than you would suspect. } 
13. Rfe1 { Playing a rook to the open file is very natural. } Be6 { Black just develops. } 
14. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3e4,Gg3f5]} { The natural route for the knight. } g6 { Takes the f5-square away. Now there only remains e4 for the g3-knight. } 
15. Ne4 Qd8 
16.-- ( { Protecting f6. White is running out of targets. Best is probably to simplify with } 16.Nc5 b6 17.Nxe6 Nxe6 18.Rad1 Qd6 { , but afterwards the position is balanced. Black will get counterplay on the kingside. First we improve with moves like ...Kg7 and ...Rad8. Then we'll look for an opportunity to start advancing the pawns on the kingside or to use the f4-square. Finally, there is always the break ...c5. } )
