1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 { The modern mainline. White takes space! } c5 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { 'There was revolution in the air' sang Bob Dylan long ago in one of my favourite songs, Tangled up in Blue. This is it! I recommend the dynamic counterstrike } 3...c5!? { instead of the real Caro-Kann move . This is actually a major shift, almost a completely new life. I have always been faithful to } ) ( 3...Bf5 { , and I've recommended it in my two books and I still like the move. After all, it is a positional dream move, and isn't that what the Caro-Kann is all about: getting the light-squared bishop out with a sound position?

Well, the short answer is yes. Here is the longer explanation. } ) ( 3...Bf5 { is fine, but these days White cleverly plays quiet lines with a sound positional foundation against it instead of going for some premature aggressive set-ups. I am talking about lines like } ) ( 3...Bf5 4.h4 h5 5.Bd3 Bxd3 6.Qxd3 { or } { 4.Nf3 e6 5.Be2 (The Short variation) or 4.Nd2 e6 5.Nb3 , which is directed against Black's c5 break. Black is probably ok in all these lines, but you have to suffer a bit because of White's extra space and I don't think that Black gets that many winning chances. } ) ( { After the dynamic } 3...c5!? { everything is different. Already after three moves there is a lot of tension in the position, and both players need to be sharp and make concrete decisions in order not to end up worse. Being well-prepared, I think that this approach gives us much more chances to come out on top after the opening, although I am well aware that a bad move instantly will spell disaster for Black. Theoretically } ) ( 3...c5!? { is fine, in my opinion, and I think it is worth the risk. } ) 
4. c4 { White intensifies the fight in the centre. } cxd4 ( { It is good to take at once. Does White really want to take back with the queen? } 4...Nc6 { could also be played. } ) 
5. Qxd4 e6 {[%cal Gb8c6][%csl Gd4]} { Simple and good. Next we play ...Nc6, gaining time on the white queen. } 
6. cxd5 Nc6 { The d-pawn is pinned! } 
7. Bb5 { OK, the knight is also pinned! } Qxd5! { The ending is fine. } 
8. Qxd5 exd5 { Black has an isolated d-pawn, but it is not weak at all. You could also call it a passed pawn! Most important, Black can put the pieces on good active squares. } 
9. Nf3 ( { After } 9.Nc3 Bb4 $146 { next comes ...Nge7. This must be fine for Black. } ) Bg4 { Let's play actively. } 
10. Nd4 {[%csl Gc6]} Nge7 {[%cal Ga7a6]} { Black is ready to break the pin with ...a6. } 
11. Bg5 {[%csl Ge7]} { White threatens to take on e7 and then on c6. This has been played in an email game. } a6! { Now White is in trouble. Their aggression has backfired! } 
12. Nxc6 Nxc6 
13. Ba4 { This was played in the aforementioned email game. Now I'd suggest the following continuation. } h6 $146  
14. Bf4 b5 
15. Bd1 Be6 
16.-- ( { We avoid simplifications. Black has the initiative. A sample line goes } 16.O-O g5 17.Bg3 Bc5 18.Nc3 Nd4 { and White has no easy moves. } )
