Well, the short answer is yes. Here is the longer explanation. } ) ( 3...Bf5 { is fine, but these days White cleverly plays quiet lines with a sound positional foundation against it instead of going for some premature aggressive set-ups. I am talking about lines like } ) ( 3...Bf5 4.h4 h5 5.Bd3 Bxd3 6.Qxd3 { or } { 4.Nf3 e6 5.Be2 (The Short variation) or 4.Nd2 e6 5.Nb3 , which is directed against Black's c5 break. Black is probably ok in all these lines, but you have to suffer a bit because of White's extra space and I don't think that Black gets that many winning chances. } ) ( { After the dynamic } 3...c5!? { everything is different. Already after three moves there is a lot of tension in the position, and both players need to be sharp and make concrete decisions in order not to end up worse. Being well-prepared, I think that this approach gives us much more chances to come out on top after the opening, although I am well aware that a bad move instantly will spell disaster for Black. Theoretically } ) ( 3...c5!? { is fine, in my opinion, and I think it is worth the risk. } ) 
4. dxc5 { Clearly the most played move and also the critical. } e6! {[%cal Gf8c5]} ( { This is the right response. Black wants to take the pawn back with ...Bxc5. Playing } 4...e6 { offends many Caro-Kann players because it leaves the c8-bishop behind the pawn and is more French than Caro-Kann! This is true, but let me briefly tell you why it is necessary. } ) ( 4...Nc6 { has been tried a lot. Unfortunately, it doesn't work. Simply protecting the e5-pawn with } 5.f4 { is much better for White. Also, the old line } { 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.c3 e6 7.Be3 is just good for White.

The result is that many hardcore Caro-Kann players have abandoned the 3...c5 line and gone for the more positional 3...Bf5 instead. In this course I aim to rehabilitate 3...c5! } { Let's return to the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.dxc5 e6! White plays a French with an extra move, you can claim. It could arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.e5 c5 4.dxc5 , and then it would be Black to move.

Yes, that is all true, but in the pure French, White would never take on c5! In the French, everybody plays the much stronger 4.c3 , just securing the centre, so in our version White has already taken on c5. This is important. I guess you can say that White has an extra move, but they have used that move to start with an inferior plan!

OK, all philosophy aside, let's be more concrete. There is a reason this is the modern mainline. With 4.dxc5, White manages to put pressure on Black's position and often gets a dangerous initiative. I will show that with well-timed and precise counterstrikes, Black is very much alive and kicking, and can fight for the full point! Many of the positions are double-edged, but that is exactly what we strive for, and theoretically Black is doing fine.

I have to warn you! There are many complicated lines, and the 4.dxc5 chapter is the longest and most difficult in the whole course. What is important, when you start employing this repertoire in your own games, is that you know some of the critical lines by heart - at least the beginning of these lines! - and that you have a feel for White's plans and how to interfere with them. You don't need to remember everything. Nobody remembers everything, at least not a while after they've studied an opening! I am sure the bravery of entering such sharp positions will be rewarded. } ) 
5. Qg4 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg4g7][%csl Gg7]} { An aggressive queen sortie. By attacking the g7-pawn, White obviously wants to prevent Black from directly playing ...Bxc5. The downside is that the queen itself is exposed. } h5! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Gg4]} { Where should the queen go? } 
6. Qg3 Nc6 ( { I prefer to start with this developing move. } 6...h4 { could be met by } 7.Qc3 { when White defends the c5-pawn. } ) 
7. Nf3 h4! { Now it comes. } 
8. Qf4 Bxc5 
9. Bd3 f5! ( { Black tries to secure the kingside. The move } 9...h3 { deserves attention too. } ) 
10. g4 ( { White must open some lines. Taking on f6 would just help Black, as after } 10.exf6 Qxf6 { , Black is very active. } ) Nge7 
11. gxf5 Nxf5 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 
12.-- ( { Black is fine. It is safe to castle next. An email game continued } 12.Qg4 O-O 13.O-O Qc7 14.Bf4 Qf7 15.Ng5 Qg6 { and Black was better. } )
