3. exd5 cxd5 { The Exchange variation is a very popular choice at all levels. The pawn structure is defined and an interesting maneuvering game can begin. } 
4. c4 ( { This is one of White's most direct approaches against the Caro-Kann. Named after the imaginative Russian player Vasily Panov, the move } 4.c4 { appeals to white players who strive for the initiative and like to play with active pieces. Often it leads to strategically interesting positions, where White has an isolated d-pawn. It was a favourite of the legendary Soviet World Champion Mikhail Botvinnik and also a dangerous weapon in the hands of attacking players like Judit Polgar. In recent years the popularity of the Panov has faded somewhat because Black has found some really good set-ups. } ) Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
5. Nc3 Nc6! { The best move in my opinion. It leaves all options open depending how white reacts. } 
