7. cxd5 { This is a normal move in many lines in the Panov, and the most likely response from White players if you surprise them with 6...a6. Here a hidden point of 6...a6 will soon be revealed! As we've seen, White has a bunch of other decent moves available, which is rather logical considering that 6...a6 is a pretty slow move. But please don't despair: Black has adequate responses ready against all of them! } Nxd5 
8. Qb3 {[%csl Gd5]} { This is the move I would expect you to face the most, because White plays like this against the standard 6...Bg4. As I promised, we have a surprising idea up our sleeve. } Be6! {[%cal Ge6b3][%csl Rb3]} { A surprising way to deal with the hanging knight. Suddenly White's queen doesn't feel safe. } 
9. Ng5! {[%cal Gg5e6]} { Counter-attacking our bishop is best. } ( 9.Qxb7 Na5 { is a great trap, winning White's queen! @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p2pppp/p1n1b3/3n4/3P4/1QN2N2/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Bc4 Na5 is also bad for White. } ) Nxd4 { Of course we take the free central pawn. } 
10. Qa4+ Nc6 
11. Nxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Ge6,Ge7]} { White has positional compensation for the pawn if they play some precise moves. Still we should be more than satisfied with the opening so far. } 
12. Be2 g6 
13. O-O Bg7 { This is the critical position of the line starting with 9.Ng5. } 
14. Bg4 {[%csl Ge6]} { Now Black needs to react with both precision and imagination! } Nxc3 
15. bxc3 Bxc3 $146  ( 15...O-O 16.Rb1 { is promising for White. } ) 
16. Rb1 Qd4! {[%cal Gd4a4,Gd4g4][%csl Rg4,Ra4]} { The point. This way Black forces the exchange of some more pieces, after which we can get castled and safeguard our king. Black is fine. } 
