1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. f3 { The Fantasy variation. This is a very popular way to meet the Caro-Kann at club level, but it occasionally pops up in all kind of tournaments. For instance, I have faced it against a strong grandmaster in the European Team Championship.

White just defends the e4-pawn and is ready to recapture with the f-pawn, so there is no chance Black will be able to get the bishop out to f5. The Fantasy can lead to very tricky play within a few moves, so you better be prepared! } e6 {[%mdl 32768]} { Solid and sound. Now it is a kind of French with a white pawn on f3, which is very unusual and something we can hope to exploit. OK, our pawn is on c6 too, but that is not really a drawback, it's merely a loss of time once we get the typical break ...c5 in. } ( { In my previous work I have recommended the sharp and very direct } 3...dxe4 4.fxe4 e5 { , but now I am not so sure, because the arising complications can be quite hard to handle. I am talking about } 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.c3 Nd7 7.Bd3 Ngf6 8.O-O Bd6 { with an interesting position that probably is balanced, but is definitely easier to play as White, who often gets the initiative. Long story short: It is a tough line to master and White scores really well. Let's try something completely different! } ) 
4. Nc3 { The most natural move. } Nd7 ( { A cool move. Black stays flexible. The main move is the French-like } 4...Bb4 { , but } ) ( 4...Nd7 { is much harder for White to meet. Depending on what White does we can still play ...Bb4, but often a quick ...Qb6 will be very strong. Also, 4...Nd7 prepares the typical positional strike ...dxe4 followed by ...e5. } ) 
5. Nge2 Qb6! {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6g1][%csl Gc1]} { A superb move. Black flirts with the mentioned ...dxe4 followed by ...e5 plan, but first improves the queen. On b6 it stares down at b2 and forces White to keep the bishop at home, and it also stands on a fantastic diagonal if the centre opens up. } 
6. a3 { This prevents ...Bb4, but also allows White to move the bishop out from c1. Then ...Qxb2 would cost us the queen after Na4. } dxe4! 
7. fxe4 e5 {[%csl Gd4]} 
8. dxe5 Bc5! {[%cal Gc5f2][%csl Ge1]} { This is a nice line that shows the danger White faces when Black executes the ...dxe4 plan. } 
9. Ng3 Bf2+ 
10. Ke2 Nxe5 {[%cal Gc8g4]} { Threatening ...Bg4+. It will be over in just a few more moves! } 
11. Nf5 Bxf5 
12. exf5 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d1][%csl Rd1]} { White can resign. Let's see a few sample lines: }
13.-- ( 13.Na4 { attacks Black's queen. You can move it, but the simplest for the practical player is to just take material: } 13...Rxd1 14.Nxb6 Rxc1 15.Rxc1 Bxb6 { . } ) ( { After } 13.Bd2 { more or less everything wins. } 13...Nc4 { is clear enough. } )
