[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "Classical Variation: Overview"]
[Black "Classical Variation: Introduction"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41961353"]

{ Traditionally, the mainline of the Caro-Kann has been the so-called Classical variation. It is still extremely popular at all levels, and it's the right place to start our deep investigation of the modern Caro-Kann. This is because it is precisely in the Classical variation that some new discoveries for Black have been found, ideas that have revitalized the entire opening! } 1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 { White simply protects the e-pawn. } dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6! ( { This is the starting position of the Classical approach. Now Black's standard move has always been } 4...Bf5 { , which is no surprise: the clever Caro-Kann strategy is to get the light-squared bishop out before the diagonal is closed with e6. The positionally very sound } ) ( 4...Bf5 { was also my choice in my 2010 book The Caro-Kann: Grandmaster Repertoire. } ) { This is the modern dynamic move. } ( 4...Bf5 { In the aforementioned book I focussed especially on the long mainline: } 5.Ng3 Bg6 6.h4 h6 7.Nf3 Nd7 8.h5 Bh7 9.Bd3 Bxd3 10.Qxd3 e6 11.Bd2 Ngf6 12.O-O-O Be7 { followed by ...O-O. Black's position is rather passive but very resilient, and often some counter-chances arise.

Although I have a lot of sympathy for this line theoretically, I must admit that whenever I played it myself I felt a little uneasy. It wasn't so much White's extra space - that is an inherent feature of the Caro-Kann - but more that White's moves were just so simple. I prefer to make the life of my opponents more difficult and I would also like to play a little more direct instead of just waiting. } ) ( 4...Nd7 { Black prepares ...Ngf6. This move is a favourite of the legendary Russian World Champion Karpov. I have also played it several times, for instance against the strong Dutch grandmaster Timman. The critical line goes: } 5.Ng5 Ngf6 6.Bd3 e6 7.N1f3 Bd6 8.Qe2 h6 9.Ne4 Nxe4 10.Qxe4 Qc7 11.Qg4 Kf8 { .

My game was drawn, by the way. In the talk afterwards I could sense that Timman wasn't that impressed with Black's opening play. I found that somewhat surprising, since Karpov had used this variation in several games against Timman in their famous World Championship match. So I confronted Timman with that fact, and asked him why Karpov kept playing the line if it was inferior. 'Because he has bad seconds', was the prompt answer! I think it is still playable for Black, but losing the right to castle is rather drastic and not for everybody. Also, like in the 4...Bf5 line, it is White who calls the shots and Black who has to defend. } ) 
5. Nxf6+ ( 5.Ng3 { tries to take the game in a different direction. It loses time and the knight is not really well placed on g3, so it shouldn't worry Black. } ) exf6! { The new hot line. } ( { The old } 5...gxf6 { has gone out of fashion. A simple way to play for White is } 6.c3 Bf5 7.Nf3 e6 8.g3 { and the bishop will be strong on g2. Black hasn't been able to come up with a completely satisfactory set-up. } ) ( { Retaking on f6 with } 5...exf6 { looks suspicious. Why give White a nice pawn majority on the queenside almost for free? Practice has shown that it is not so easy for White to exploit this positional advantage, and you can add that although it doesn't seem like much, Black's extra pawn on the kingside gives good protection for the king. The real benefit of ...exf6 is that the black pieces have access to good squares, and it will be easy to get castled. } ) 
6. c3 ( { Just like against 5...gxf6, this is White's best. White has other options of course, like } 6.Nf3 { and . They will be covered in the theory section. } ) Bd6 { A nice square. } 
7. Bd3 O-O 
8. Qc2 {[%csl Gh7]} { Hitting h7 and forcing Black to weaken the king's position. } Re8+ 
9. Ne2 h5!? ( { This is the spectacular move that renewed interest in Caro-Kann. Moving the h-pawn up the board is the new normal in many openings. In this particular case you would imagine that it weakens Black's kingside more than it helps. In the beginning of games with } 9...h5 { , White automatically castled long and expected to use the h5-pawn as a hook to open lines on the kingside. However, it turned out that it was not so simple, and Black's counterplay came surprisingly fast. Then White started to play more positionally with short castling, which I believe is the best. Also here the black position is firm, so 9...h5!? has stood the test of time, at least so far. } ) ( { I recommended this move in the book Playing the Caro-Kann, which was published in 2021. It was a cool and fresh approach at the time. In this course I recommend the much simpler } 9...h6! { . This old move had a bad reputation for a long time. White won some impressive attacking games, and also positionally the weak f5-square was a concern. However, many of the findings after } ) ( 9...h5 { can also be used after } ) ( 9...h6 { , especially if White castles long, and the crushing victories are easy to improve upon.

Actually, I believe that White's best approach is to castle short, but then it is much easier to play the black position with the pawn on h6 instead of on h5. And then there is also the practical value: These days White expects . Probably they don't take } ) ( 9...h6 { seriously, or have almost forgotten that this move exists! } ) 
