24. Qa6 { Looks active, but White is not really threatening anything. } g5! {[%cal Gg8g7,Gh7h5]} { Black takes the initiative. The play on the kingside can be prepared with moves like ...Kg7 and ...h5. } 
25. Nh2 { This allows Black to transform the position to a simple strong knight vs. bad bishop scenario. } Bxh2+! 
26. Kxh2 Kg7 
27. Kg1 Rxe1+! 
28. Rxe1 Rb8! {[%cal Gb8b2]} { Great technical play by the World Champion. The e-file isn't worth much, while the black rook can enter White's position on the queenside. } 
29. Qd3 Rb2 { Already White is tied up and forced to defend passively. } 
30. a5 h6 
31. Bc1 ( 31.Rb1 Qb7 32.Rxb2 Qxb2 { is also pretty depressing, but White could then try to build a fortress. } ) Ra2 
32. Bd2 Qb7 {[%cal Gb7b2]} { The queen is also ready to penetrate the white position. } 
33. Re8 ( { Desperately seeking counterplay. The passive } 33.Rd1 { could be met by } 33...a6 { followed by ...Qb5 with a strategically winning position. } ) Qb2 
34. Be1 Nf4 
35. Qa6 {[%cal Ga6c8,Ge8g8][%csl Gg7]} { Intending Qc8. } Qxd4 ( { Imprecise. It gives White a last chance. Black could have won with } 35...Ra1! 36.Qc8 Ng6! { White has a single check on g8, but nothing more! } ) 
36. Qc8! Ng6 
37. Qxc6? ( { White should have tried } 37.Rg8+ Kh7 38.Rxg6! { Perhaps it isn't quite good enough: The black king can escape the checks, but the game goes on. } 38...Kxg6! 39.Qg8+ Kf5 40.Qc8+ Ke4 41.Qxc6+ Kd3 42.Qf3+ Kc2 43.c6 { Surprisingly the engines only give Black a small plus! } ) Ra1 { Now everything is smooth sailing for Black again. } 
38. Qe4 ( 38.Re3 Qb4 { wasn't better. } ) Qxc5 { With a pawn more and a very active position there is no longer any doubt about the result. Black just wins. } 
39. Kh2 h5 
40. Qe3 Qc6 { Black is the one attacking so the queens should stay on the board. } 
41. Bc3 Ra4 
42. f3 Ra2 { Now g2 is a new target. } 
43. Kh1 Rc2 
44. Be1 Qb5 
45. Bg3 h4 
46. Bh2 Qb1+! 
