[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "1) Classical: Rare Lines"]
[Black "Classical: 5.Nxf6+ with 6.Be3 #3"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41963630"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { In this chapter we will look at some of the more random tries. Firstly, White is not forced to take on f6! Moving the knight away from e4 is illogical: it loses time and refrains from inflicting some structural damage on Black's position. Yet it avoids mainline theory and that is a benefit in itself for some players. } 
5. Nxf6+ exf6 { White's three main moves are c3, Nf3 and Bc4. Here we will check the rare alternatives. } 
6. Be3 { Of all the minor moves in the chapter, this is clearly the most interesting theoretically. } Qb6!? {[%cal Gb6b2]} { Black attacks b2 and tries to disturb White's fluid development. } ( { The natural and also by far the most played } 6...Bd6 { can be met by } 7.Bd3 O-O 8.Ne2 Re8 9.O-O Nd7 { . This is almost identical to the modern way of handling the mainline, which we will see in a subsequent chapter. The difference here is that White hasn't spent a tempo on the move c3, and can instead try } 10.c4 { , which has scored an impressive 70%. } ) ( { Black also has the interesting } 6...Na6!? 7.a3 Bd6 8.Bd3 O-O 9.Ne2 Re8 10.O-O Bg4 { as played by Magnus Carlsen. } ) 
7. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e8]} { Now Black must watch out for a discovered check. That is why you can't take on b2. } ( { The passive } 7.Qc1 { can be met by } 7...c5 { with good counterplay. } ) Bd6! { A cool move. Apparently the threatened discovered check is not so much of a threat after all! } 
8. d5 {[%cal Ge3b6]} { White opens the position. } ( 8.c3 O-O { is fine for Black. } ) Qc7 { Again the discovered check can be handled! } 
9. Bc5+ {[%cal Ge2e8]} { The best way to give the check. } ( 9.Bb6+ Qe7 { is nothing, and @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/ppq2ppp/2pb1p2/3P4/8/4B3/PPP1QPPP/R3KBNR w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Bxa7+ Kf8 gives Black a strong initiative. } ) Kf8 
10. Bxd6+ Qxd6 
11. O-O-O! ( 11.dxc6 Nxc6 12.Rd1 Qc5 { is good for Black. The white kingside is still in its initial position. } ) cxd5 
12. Qd2 {[%csl Gd5]} { White will win the pawn back, but Black will get the pieces out with a satisfactory game. } Nc6 
13. Qxd5 Qe7 { White doesn't have anything better than to go into an ending with Qd6, either now or on the following moves, but Black equalizes without any problems. } 
14. Bb5 $146  ( 14.Qd6 Be6 { probably transposes. } ) Be6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
15. Qd6 Ne5! {[%cal Ge7d6,Gf8e7]} 
16.-- ( { Black is fine. The queens will be exchanged and the king will get to e7. Here is a sample line: } 16.Ne2 Qxd6 17.Rxd6 Ke7 18.Rhd1 a6 19.Ba4 Rad8 20.Rb6!? Rxd1+ 21.Kxd1 Rd8+ 22.Ke1 Bc8= { . Next, Black will most likely play ...Rd6 and get rid of the annoying white rook. } )
