[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "2) Classical: 6.Nf3"]
[Black "Classical 6.Nf3 with 7.Be2 #1"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41961409"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 
5. Nxf6+ exf6 
6. Nf3 { This has been played a lot. Not so surprisingly perhaps, since it is an obvious move. In my opinion, the popularity is not justified if we go a little deeper. On f3 the knight is not at all well-placed. The black doubled pawn, more specifically the f6-pawn, controls both g5 and e5 and White's own pawn on d4 takes another square away. If you add all this up, then it is clear that the knight on f3 doesn't have much potential - it just stands there. Of course, in the opening much is about getting the pieces out and the knight move fulfills that obligation. Next, the bishop can go to e2... But that is also a passive piece then.

Long story short: The knight is better on e2 than f3. Then it can go to g3 and perhaps even jump to the juicy f5-square, and from e2 it also helps to play Bf4 and contest Black's strong Bd6. } ( { That is why } 6.c3 { followed by Bd3 and Ne2 is the best white set-up. See more about that in the 6.c3 chapter [/course/261638/6]! } ) Bd6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. Be2 { Solid. This is almost too safe, and Black has pretty easy play. } O-O 
8. O-O Re8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f8,Gf8g6]} { The ideal place for the rook and it also vacates the f8-square so Black can regroup the knight with Nb8-d7-f8 and later to g6. This piece constellation with ...Re8 and ...Nf8 is also seen in the Queen's Gambit Declined, and is a perfect example of how to navigate when you are lacking space. After the knight is out of the way on f8, the light-squared bishop can come out of its shelter and establish itself on e6 or f5, or even g4 if White has not prevented this with h3. Finally, Black can play ...Qd7 and ...Rad8 when all pieces are very harmoniously developed. } 
9. c4 ( { Many of the moves can be played in a different move order. For instance, } 9.Be3 Nd7 10.c4 { transposes back to 9.c4. } ) ( 9.Re1 Nd7 10.Be3 Nf8 { will also eventually get us to where we want to be, because the moves from both sides are so natural: } 11.Qd2 Ng6 12.c4 Bf5 { with another transposition [/variation/41961410/#/12/b]. } ) Nd7 
10. Be3 ( 10.Bd3 Nf8 11.h3 Ng6 { was seen in a remarkable game between Nepomniachtchi and Carlsen, where the Norwegian Wonder showed the full potential of Black's kingside play. Check it out in the Model Games section [/variation/42271877/#/11/b]. } ) Nf8 { Black has the standard formation. } 
11. d5 {[%csl Gd5]} { Advancing in the centre is sort of desireable. Here, however, it doesn't open the centre and create a nice majority on the queenside, because Black can keep the position closed. } c5! {[%csl Gd6]} { Black has a good game. The bishop on d6 is a perfect blockading piece. It doesn't just stop the white d-pawn from advancing further, it also stares down at the white king's position, and a black offensive on the kingside is very much on the agenda. } 
12. b4 { This violent attempt to open up the position and get the central pawns rolling is firmly refuted. } cxb4 
13. c5 Rxe3! 
14. fxe3 Bxc5 { With two pawns for the exchange and complete dark-square control, Black is strategically almost winning. } 
*

