1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 
5. Nxf6+ exf6 
6. Nf3 { This has been played a lot. Not so surprisingly perhaps, since it is an obvious move. In my opinion, the popularity is not justified if we go a little deeper. On f3 the knight is not at all well-placed. The black doubled pawn, more specifically the f6-pawn, controls both g5 and e5 and White's own pawn on d4 takes another square away. If you add all this up, then it is clear that the knight on f3 doesn't have much potential - it just stands there. Of course, in the opening much is about getting the pieces out and the knight move fulfills that obligation. Next, the bishop can go to e2... But that is also a passive piece then.

Long story short: The knight is better on e2 than f3. Then it can go to g3 and perhaps even jump to the juicy f5-square, and from e2 it also helps to play Bf4 and contest Black's strong Bd6. } ( { That is why } 6.c3 { followed by Bd3 and Ne2 is the best white set-up. See more about that in the 6.c3 chapter [/course/261638/6]! } ) Bd6 
7. Bd3 { The natural set-up. } O-O 
8. O-O Bg4! {[%cal Gg4d1]} { Exploiting that White didn't play h3. The pin is quite annoying. Of course, Black could also play } { 9...Re8 followed by ...Nd7 and ...Nf8 with a normal position. } 
9. h3 { It makes sense to ask the bishop what it wants. } ( 9.c3 Nd7 { and @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp3ppp/2pb1p2/8/3P2b1/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Re1 Re8 10.Rxe8+ Qxe8 both lead to similar play as in the mainline. } ) Bh5 
10. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e8]} { White takes the e-file before Black can play Re8. } ( 10.c4 Re8 { will most likely transpose to other lines. } ) Re8 ( { Simple and good. } 10...Nd7 { is also fine. } ) 
11. Rxe8+ Qxe8 
12. Be3 Nd7 { Black's moves come very easy. } 
13. g4 { A tough decison to make. It weakens the kingside. On the other hand, White gets out of the pin. } Bg6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
14. Nh4 ( 14.Bxg6 hxg6 { is good for Black. } ) Bxd3 $146  { This new move is a simple solution. } 
15. Qxd3 g6 {[%csl Gf5]} ( { Covering the f5-square. Also just } 15...Rd8 { is fine. } ) 
16. c4 Rd8 {[%cal Gd7f8]} { Black will play ...Nf8 and stand in a good defensive formation. Later, all the weak squares that have appeared in the wake of White's offensive pawn play can hopefully be used to get the upper hand. } 
