7. Qe2+! Be7! ( { This is it. The check comes just before Black can castle, and is a bit awkward to face. The main problem is that the bishop on c4 prevents the answer } 7...Be6 { , so Black must choose between the ending after } ) ( 7...Qe7 { or losing a tempo with the bishop and settle for . Moving the king is out of the question. } { If White just develops, Black has no problems. 7.Nf3 transposes to the 6.Nf3 chapter [/variation/41961412/#/7/w], and 7.Ne2 looks mysterious with the bishop on c4 instead of d3. Black can go 7...O-O 8.O-O Re8 with a normal, fine position. } ) { The best practical decision. Throughout this course I think I have revealed a fondness for endings in general and also here I would be tempted to allow it. } ( 7...Qe7 8.Qxe7+ Kxe7 { seems absolutely playable. Yes, positionally White has the superior pawn structure, but it will be hard to advance the queenside majority, and in the meantime Black's pieces will take up good positions. A sample line goes } 9.Ne2 Be6 10.Bd3 Rd8 11.O-O Nd7 12.Re1 Nb6 13.c3 Kf8 { and Black is OK. } ) ( { Still, I recommend } 7...Be7! { True, the bishop belongs on d6, but it can always return to that square after we have castled. It loses time, but White's queen is not optimal on the open e-file and may be attacked by ...Re8. All in all, it is kind of an exchange of tempi! } ) 
8. Nf3 { The natural continuation. White prepares short castling. } O-O {[%mdl 32768]} 
9. O-O Bd6 {[%csl Gd6]} ( { The optimal square for the bishop. It is also possible to leave it on e7 for the time being and go on with the development: } 9...Nd7!? 10.Re1 Re8 11.c3 Nf8 12.Bf4 Be6 { with a balanced position. } ) 
10. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e8]} ( { Taking the e-file. } 10.h3 Re8 11.Be3 { or 11.Qd3 a5 } 11...Nd7 12.Bb3 Nf8 { is a set-up we know by now! Black is fine. } ) a5!? {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c7,Gf8e8][%csl Ge8]} { The first phase of the opening is over. Both sides have castled. Now Black needs to come up with a scheme for the next phase. What should the pieces aim for? The lack of space makes it hard for Black to achieve an optimal set-up. The two pieces that should be developed are the c8-bishop and the b8-knight. The bishop can go out to g4, but for concrete reasons this doesn't solve the problems. The knight can go to d7 as usual, but there it blocks the bishop, and since White controls the e-file there is no ...Re8 and ...Nf8.

The solution is to send it in a different direction. The knight should go to a6 and c7. Then Black can contest the e-file and the bishop can go to e6. } ( 10...Na6 { at once allows } 11.Bxa6 { , which ruins the pawn chain. Black gets the bishops in return and it seems playable. White is probably still slightly better after } { 12.Bd2 a5 , so I prefer to make a small preparation before playing ...Na6. } ) ( { The tempting } 10...Bg4 { gives White a clear positional plus after the precise } 11.Qe4! Bh5 12.Nh4! ) 
11. c3 ( { This stabilizes the centre and takes b4 from the knight. After } 11.a4 Na6 { or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p3ppp/2pb1p2/p7/2BP4/5N2/PPP1QPPP/R1B1R1K1 w - a6 0 11@@EndFEN@@ 11.Bd3 Na6 White should play 12.c3 anyway. } ) Na6 {[%cal Ga6c7]} { We have a balanced position. Black gets the pieces out in a harmonious way, which is clear as soon as the knight lands on c7. Taking on a6 is not really an option for White when Black can just take back with the rook, so White has to come up with something else, which is not that easy. Their pawn structure is nice, but also rather rigid, and the bishop on c1 lacks a good square. } 
12. Bd3 Nc7 
13. Qc2 {[%csl Gh7]} { Attacking h7 is a good positional plan. Black is forced to move a pawn in front of the king, which gives White a few extra possibilities. This is nothing serious though. } ( 13.Qe4 { would transpose to the model game [/variation/42271878/#/13/w] Sprenger - Anton Guijarro, Germany 2022. } ) g6 
14. Bh6 Re8 
15. Rxe8+ Nxe8 
16. Re1 { This is the maximum White can get: control over the only open file, a better pawn structure and more active pieces. As an email game shows, this doesn't automatically add up to an advantage. The position is in fact balanced, and after just a few more moves it becomes quite clear. } Be6 
17. c4 { White's main advantage must be their pawn majority. But can the pawns really start rolling? } Bf8 { This removes the most active white piece. } 
18. Bxf8 Kxf8 {[%cal Gd8d4]} { Black has pressure against the d4-pawn and it will be hard to advance it further. } 
19. h3 { Otherwise ...Bg4 could be annoying. } Kg7 {[%cal Ge8d6]} { The game is equal. Black can for instance put the knight on d6 with a firm position. } 
