[White "4) Classical: 6.c3 With O-O"]
[Black "Classical 6.c3 with 9.Ne2, 11.Ng3 #1"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41961496"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 
5. Nxf6+ exf6 
6. c3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2][%csl Gc3,Gd4]} { The big mainline. White strengthens the centre and prepares the optimal set-up with Bd3 and Ne2. } Bd6 
7. Bd3 O-O 
8. Qc2 {[%csl Gh7]} { This used to be played almost automatically. The attack on h7 forces Black to weaken the kingside somewhat, after which White will castle long and try to exploit the newly created weakness on the kingside to open lines and get a strong attack. In the next chapter I will investigate these positions where White castles long. Here it suffices to say that it leads to double-edged play, to put it mildly. } Re8+ {[%mdl 32768]} { A good intermediate check. } 
9. Ne2 h6!? { This old move is totally underestimated! I rediscovered it in Alex Banzea's course The Caro-Kann: Simplified. Of course, it is a well-known move. Nobody took it serious, because it really is a weakening of Black's position. White has two ways to exploit it: castle long and use the h6-pawn as a hook to open lines, or castle short and use the nice f5-square since Black won't be able to guard it with ...g6 anymore because that would lose the h6-pawn. } ( { The modern solution for Black is } 9...h5!? { . This spectacular new move made fighting players return to the Caro-Kann, and of course it was the subject of my book Playing the Caro-Kann. The move } ) ( 9...h5!? { was hot at that time, and a very fine example of when the avant-garde meets the mainstream. It has been analyzed and played a lot since then, and there is just so much theory.

An excessive amount of opening theory in general is the curse of modern chess. It is like a line from David Bowie's apocalyptic song Five Years: 'My brain hurts like a warehouse, it had no room to spare, I had to cram so many things to store everything in there'. This is a perfect description of the mental state of a chess professional! } ) ( { I started analyzing the } 9...h6 { move very deeply and came to a surprising conclusion: it is just as good as } ) ( 9...h5 { objectively speaking, but much simpler to handle and therefore a great practical choice. Furthermore, at least for now, it has a big surprise value.

In the next chapter, I will show that White's attacking chances are not as scary as once believed. Here we will look at the positional approach, where White just castles short. I think this is White's best option - just as it is against 9...h5. } ) 
10. O-O! ( { If White wants to castle short it is optimal to do it at once. Various move orders like } 10.Be3 Nd7 11.O-O { or @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3pp1/2pb1p1p/8/3P4/2PB4/PPQ1NPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10.h3 Nd7 11.O-O or @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3pp1/2pb1p1p/8/3P4/2PB4/PPQ1NPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10.Bd2 Nd7 11.O-O will inevitably lead to the same positions that arise after 10.O-O. } ) Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f8]} { The knight is on the way to f8. } 
11. Ng3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5]} { From here the knight has a great view of the super squares e4 and f5. } Nb6! {[%cal Gb6d5]} ( { A rare occasion where the black knight is not heading for f8. Actually, } 11...Nf8 { is by far the most played move. However, I am not sure what to do after . Maybe } { 12...b6 $146 13.Bd2 Qc7 with an interesting fight. } ) 
12. Bd2 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ga1e1]} { White is preparing to take the e-file. } ( 12.b3 { invites } 12...a5 { , when Black is fine after } 13.Bb2 Nd5 { . } ) Be6 ( { Even the typical Caro-kann move } 12...a5!? { could be tried. } ) 
13. Rae1 { This looks more in the style of an attacking player. } a5!? {[%cal Ga5a4][%csl Ga2]} { When the rook has left the queenside, this advance increases in strength. Black wants to play ...a4 next. } 
14. a4 { So White stops it. There is a thematic drawback, though, which is highlighted by Black's response. } Nd5 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gd5b4]} { The white pawns are rigid because if c4 comes, then the black knight can jump to b4. With the pawn still on a2, White could have made the preparatory move a3 and then kicked the knight with c4, but here that is impossible. } 
15. Qc1 {[%cal Gd2h6]} Bf8 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gb7b5]} { Defending against any Bxh6 tricks. Black is solid. Next the position can be improved with ...Qd7 and if possible a quick ...b5, with good play on the queenside. } 
