13. g4 Nb6 
14. h4 {[%cal Gg4g5][%csl Gg4]} { This is White's most direct plan: to push g5 and open a motorway towards the lonely black king. It was played in one of the old games that seemed like a refutation of the whole ...h6-setup. } Nd5! ( { Taking the pawn is risky: } 14...Bxg4 15.Rhg1 h5 16.Bf5 { and White has good compensation. } ) 
15. g5 { This was Jansa-E. Pedersen, Denmark 1983. White won in style, but Stockfish easily refutes the line. } Rxe3 $146  
16. fxe3 Nxe3 {[%csl Rc2,Rd1]} 
17.-- ( { Black wins material. The best White can get is seen in the following sample line: } 17.Bh7+ Kh8 18.Qe4 Be6! 19.d5 Bxd5 20.Rxd5 Nxd5 21.gxf6 Nxf6 22.Qxc6 Rd8 23.Bc2 Be5 { and Black is a pawn up. } )
