1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 { The modern mainline. White takes space! } c5!? ( { 'There was revolution in the air' sang Bob Dylan long ago in one of my favourite songs, Tangled up in Blue. This is it! I recommend the dynamic counterstrike } 3...c5!? { instead of the real Caro-Kann move . This is actually a major shift, almost a completely new life. I have always been faithful to } ) ( 3...Bf5 { , and I've recommended it in my two books and I still like the move. After all, it is a positional dream move, and isn't that what the Caro-Kann is all about: getting the light-squared bishop out with a sound position?

Well, the short answer is yes. Here is the longer explanation. } ) ( 3...Bf5 { is fine, but these days White cleverly plays quiet lines with a sound positional foundation against it instead of going for some premature aggressive set-ups. I am talking about lines like } ) ( 3...Bf5 4.h4 h5 5.Bd3 Bxd3 6.Qxd3 { or } { 4.Nf3 e6 5.Be2 (The Short variation) or 4.Nd2 e6 5.Nb3 , which is directed against Black's c5 break. Black is probably ok in all these lines, but you have to suffer a bit because of White's extra space and I don't think that Black gets that many winning chances. } ) ( { After the dynamic } 3...c5!? { everything is different. Already after three moves there is a lot of tension in the position, and both players need to be sharp and make concrete decisions in order not to end up worse. Being well-prepared, I think that this approach gives us much more chances to come out on top after the opening, although I am well aware that a bad move instantly will spell disaster for Black. Theoretically } ) ( 3...c5!? { is fine, in my opinion, and I think it is worth the risk. } ) 
4. dxc5 ( { Probably the best move and certainly the one you will face most often in practice. White has tried a bunch of other moves. Here I will just list some of them: } 4.Nf3 { , } ) ( 4.c3 { , } ) ( 4.c4 { , } ) ( 4.Bb5+ { , and .

In general, perhaps apart from } ) ( 4.c3 { , White responds with active, very direct moves that strive for the initiative. Black, on the other hand, hits the white centre and hopes to get active counterplay from the get-go, and there is always the inherent Caro-Kann soundness to fall back upon if the play slows down and both sides concentrate on development and getting castled.

All in all, with 3...c5!? you are guaranteed a full blown fight right from the start and this mindset fits perfectly with the general intention of this course. } ) *

