1. e4 c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 c5 
4. c3 Nc6 
5. Nf3 cxd4 
6. cxd4 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1][%csl Gd4,Gg4]} { Black gets the Caro-Kann bishop out. The next step is to develop the kingside, which always is a little difficult due to White's strong e5-pawn that takes f6 away from our knight. } 
7. Be2 e6 
8. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2f3]} { To be able to take back on f3 with a knight. } Bb4! {[%csl Ge7]} { Both the bishop and the knight want to be on e7. This is impossible, of course, so the bishop sacrifices itself for a higher cause. The real revelation is that this is justified positionally! } 
9. O-O Bxd2! 
10. Qxd2 Nge7 { The pieces get out nicely. Who was screaming about lack of space? } 
11. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} { Planning Bb2. } Qa5! { Excellent judgement. In the ending, White's extra space is not so important. } 
12. Qxa5 ( { White could hardly avoid the queen exchange. } 12.Qb2 Nf5 { is good for Black, who already threatens to take on f3 and win the d4-pawn. } ) Nxa5 
13. Bb2 Rc8 
14. Rac1 Nac6 { The ending is balanced. } 
15. Rfd1 a6 
16. h3 Bxf3! { This must have come as a surprise for White. Black is prepared to play with two knights vs. two bishops. In fact, the knights have good potential, while the bishops lack something to attack. } 
17. Bxf3 Kd7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gc6b4]} { The centre is closed so it is a maneuvering game. Black can play ...Nf5 next. If White prevents this with g4, then the knight takes a new route and jumps to f4 from g6. On the other flank, Black can attack the a2-pawn with ...Nb4. If White tries to prevent this with a3, then ...Na5 attacks b3, and if b4, then the knight gets a nice outpost on c4. } 
18. Be2 Nf5 { Threatening to take on d4. } 
19. Bg4 ( { Probably better was } 19.Kf1= { . } ) Nb4! {[%csl Ga2]} { Black isn't bothered by the possibility of Bxf5 because that would leave White with a bad bishop on b2 vs. a strong knight, as we will see in the game. } 
20. a3 Rxc1! { Very precise. Now White can't take back with the rook. } 
21. Bxc1 ( 21.Rxc1 Nd3 22.Rc2 Nxb2 23.Bxf5 exf5 24.Rxb2 Rc8 { and Black controls the only open file and has excellent winning chances. } ) Nc6 {[%csl Gd4]} 
22. Bxf5 ( { A big concession. Protecting the pawn made sense. Black is very comfortable after } 22.Bb2 Rc8 { , but maybe White can defend. } ) exf5 
23. Rd3 ( { Or } 23.Bb2 Rc8 24.Rc1 Na5! 25.Rxc8 Kxc8 26.b4 Nc4 { with a great knight and a lot of weak light squares in the white camp. } ) Rc8 
24. Bd2 Na7 {[%cal Gc8c2]} { Preparing ...Rc2. } 
25. g4 ( 25.Rc3 Nb5 26.Rxc8 Kxc8 { is worse than before because two pawns are hanging and White can't defend both of them. } ) fxg4 
26. hxg4 Rc2 
27. Kg2 Nc6 
28. Kg3 Ke6 { White is tied up. The only question is if Black can break through. } 
29. a4 Rb2 
30. f3 Rb1 { The black rook is very active, while the white one just stands there and waits. } 
31. Kf2 Rh1 
32. Kg2 Rd1 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gd1d3]} { Threatening ...Nb4. } 
33. Kf2 g6! {[%cal Gh7h5]} ( { Preparing to create a passed pawn with ...h5. } 33...Nb4 { doesn't work because of } 34.Ke2 { . } ) 
34. Ke2 ( 34.g5 Nb4 { Now it works! } 35.Ke2 Nxd3 36.Kxd1 Kf5 { Black wins. } 37.Ke2 Nf4+ { It is game over. } ) Rb1 
35. Kf2 ( { Not } 35.g5 Rxb3! { . } ) h5! 
36. Kg3 Rd1 { Pinning again. } 
37. gxh5 ( 37.Kf2 h4 38.Ke2 h3 39.Kxd1 h2 { is a nice line that demonstrates the helplessness of White's position. } ) gxh5 
38. Kf2 h4 
39. Ke2 ( { If } 39.Kg2 Nb4! { and Black wins. } ) h3! 
40. Bf4 Rxd3 
41. Kxd3 Kf5 
42. Bh2 b5 
43. axb5 axb5 { White will quickly be in zugzwang. } 
44. Bg3 b4 
45. Bh2 Kg5 
46. Bg3 Ne7 
47. Bh2 Nf5 
0-1

