1. e4 c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 c5 
4. dxc5 { The critical move. White speeds everything up. } e6 
5. Nf3 Bxc5 
6. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Nd7 ( 6...f6! { at once is maybe the most precise, and should just transpose. } ) 
7. Bd3 ( { The active } 7.b4 Be7 8.c4 { was possible. } ) f6! {[%csl Ge5]} { The important e5-pawn is challenged. As long as the pawn stands firm in the centre, White's extra space and kingside potential are attractive features. As soon as the pawn is gone, the black pieces get access to valuable squares and the counterplay is coming. } 
8. b4! {[%cal Gc1b2]} { White wants the bishop on b2 where it fights for control over e5. } Be7! { A deep move. At first it looks like the bishop is taking the normal e7-square away from the black knight, then you realize that the knight in fact has another splendid route: it can go to h6 and then to f7 to support the siege of the e5-square. Everything is about that battle. The bishop can participate as well. If Black plays ...fxe5 followed by ...Bf6, all the pieces work together for a higher cause. } 
9. Bb2 a5! {[%csl Gb4]} { A fine little intermediate move. } 
10. b5 {[%csl Gc5]} { Now the black pieces can use the c5-square as they please. } Nh6! {[%cal Gh6f7][%csl Ge5]} { The knight is coming. } 
11. Nbd2 Nf7 {[%cal Gf7e5,Gd7e5,Gf6e5][%csl Ge5]} { e5 falls. } 
12. exf6 Bxf6 
13. Bxf6 Qxf6 
14. c4! { White keeps playing active, direct moves. } Nc5 
15. Bc2 b6! { Black is in no hurry to castle. } 
16. O-O a4! {[%csl Gb3]} { Another excellent positional move that prevents Nb3. True, White can open the e-file and give a check, but then what? } 
17. cxd5 exd5 
18. Re1+ Be6 
19. Nf1?! ( { The human move, but now Black takes over. The computer proposes } 19.Qb1! { which attacks h7. After } 19...h6 { , the move } 20.Bh7!? { is possible to prevent castling. I admit it looks artificial and probably Black should just castle to the other side with } 20...O-O-O { . It is not easy for White to get to the black king despite a lot of holes in Black's position, and I guess Black is doing just fine. } ) O-O 
20. Ne3? { This is definitely a mistake. } Ng5! {[%csl Gf3]} 
21. Nxg5 Qxg5 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd5d4]} { Black has a strong initiative. If White doesn't do anything, then ...Rad8 and probably ...d4 will follow. } 
22. Qe2 { This doesn't make it better! } d4! { White is pushed back. } 
23. Nf1 Rae8 {[%cal Ge8e2]} { Here the rook is much more active than on d8. } 
24. Rad1? { This loses at once, though the position could hardly be saved anyway. } ( 24.Ng3 Bb3! 25.Bxb3+ axb3! 26.Qc4+ Kh8 27.Rxe8 Rxe8 28.Qxd4 Rd8 29.Qc3 Qd2! 30.Qxd2 Rxd2 { and Black wins the ending. The free b-pawn decides. } ) Bd5! {[%cal Ge8e2][%csl Rg2,Re2]} { Threating mate in one, so White can't save the queen. } 
0-1

