1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 c5 { In this chapter, I will examine some of the rare lines for White. They can be quite tricky because of the high tension in the centre. Overall, Black is doing great, but you need to be on your marks. } 
4. c4 { White intensifies the fight in the centre. } cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { It is good to take at once. Does White really want to take back with the queen? } 4...Nc6 { could also be played. } ) 
5. Qxd4 e6 {[%cal Gb8c6][%csl Gd4]} { Simple and good. Next we play ...Nc6, gaining time on the white queen. } 
6. cxd5 Nc6 { The d-pawn is pinned! } 
7. Bb5 { OK, the knight is also pinned! } Qxd5! { The ending is fine. } 
8. Qxd5 exd5 { Black has an isolated d-pawn, but it is not weak at all. You could also call it a passed pawn! Most important, Black can put the pieces on good active squares. } 
9. Nf3 ( { After } 9.Nc3 Bb4 $146 { next comes ...Nge7. This must be fine for Black. } ) Bg4 { Let's play actively. } 
10. Nd4 {[%csl Gc6]} Nge7 {[%cal Ga7a6]} { Black is ready to break the pin with ...a6. } 
11. Bg5 {[%csl Ge7]} { White threatens to take on e7 and then on c6. This has been played in an email game. } a6! { Now White is in trouble. Their aggression has backfired! } 
12. Nxc6 Nxc6 
13. Ba4 { This was played in the aforementioned email game. Now I'd suggest the following continuation. } h6 $146  
14. Bf4 b5 
15. Bd1 Be6 
16.-- ( { We avoid simplifications. Black has the initiative. A sample line goes } 16.O-O g5 17.Bg3 Bc5 18.Nc3 Nd4 { and White has no easy moves. } )
