7. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3]} ( { The best square for the bishop. } 7.a3 { controls b4 and makes sure that Bd3 cannot be disturbed by ...Nb4. I suggest we just go } 7...a6 { like in the mainline. } ) ( 7.Bb5 { looks active, but after the simple } 7...Nge7 { followed by ...a6, Black has good play. } ) a6! {[%cal Gc5a7]} { A clever move that makes sure the c5-bishop always has a retreat on a7. } ( 7...Nge7 { is the normal move, but I think } 8.Na4! { could be a problem. } ) ( 7...f6 { is also often seen, but after } 8.Qe2 { White controls the e5-square and I am not convinced that Black equalizes. } ) 
8. O-O Nge7 { A very interesting position. } 
9. a3 { Prevents ...Nb4. } Qc7 {[%csl Ge5]} ( { Please don't hurry to castle! } 9...O-O? 10.Bxh7+! Kxh7 11.Ng5+ { wins for White. } ) 
10. Re1 Bd7! {[%mdl 32768]} { Black improves the position. Again, Black should not castle yet! } 
11. Na4 $146  ( { A new move that tries to take control over the dark squares. } 11.Bf4 f5! { still works for Black. } ) Ba7 
12. b4 Nd4! {[%cal Gd7a4]} 
13. Nc5 { So far so good. Here Black shouldn't be materialistic. } Nxf3+ 
14. Qxf3 Bb5! { A nice positional move. } ( { Also possible is } 14...Bxc5 15.bxc5 Qxc5 16.a4 { followed by Ba3, when White has good compensation for the pawn. This is risky for Black, but you could play @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1pqbnppp/p3p3/2PpP3/8/P2B1Q2/2P2PPP/R1B1R1K1 b kq - 0 15@@EndFEN@@ 15...Bb5! , like in the mainline, instead of taking on c5 with the queen. } ) 
15. Bxb5+ { This forcing move needs to be checked. } ( 15.Be3 O-O { and Black is fine. } ) axb5 
16. Qd3 Bxc5 
17. Qxb5+ Qd7 
18. Qxc5 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c2]} { Black regains the pawn with advantage. The white bishop is really bad while our knight has some nice posts on the light squares. } 
