1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 c5 
4. Nf3 { White chooses fast development and active piece play over structural damage. } ( { In case of } 4.Ne2 { , the practical decision is to play } 4...cxd4 { , when } 5.Nxd4 { transposes back to 4.Nf3 lines. } ) cxd4! {[%mdl 32768]} 
5. Qxd4 { Bringing the queen out is also tempting, although it is against the classical opening principles! } Nc6 
6. Qf4 ( { The best square. } 6.Bb5 e6 { followed by ...Nge7 is fine for Black. } ) g6!? {[%cal Gf8h6,Gh6c1][%csl Rc1,Rf4]} { An unusual idea. Black actually threatens ...Bh6! The line leads quickly to some fascinating positions where Black seems to be doing really well. Beware: this line is experimental and little explored. } ( 6...e6 { is the standard move, when White can reply } 7.Bd3 { or } { 7.Nc3 . } ) 
7. Nc3 d4 { The play now becomes sharp and very concrete. } 
8. Nb5 {[%csl Gd4]} { The d-pawn seems lost, but a small tactical sequence keeps material equality. } Bh6 
9. Qh4 { The queen needs to keep attacking d4. } Bxc1 
10. Rxc1 a6 
11. Nbxd4 Nxe5! {[%cal Gd8a5,Ga5e5][%csl Ge5]} { This is the nice point. True, White won the d-pawn, but Black wins the pawn on e5! } 
12. Nxe5 Qa5+ 
13. c3 Qxe5+ 
14. Be2 g5! { There are other moves, but why not force an ending? } 
15. Qg3 ( 15.Qh5 Nf6 { comes with tempo. } ) Qxg3 
16. hxg3 Nf6 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gc8d7]} { Black is fine. A plan is to play ...h5. The bishop goes to d7 and quite likely Black castles long. } 
*

