4. Nf3 { White chooses fast development and active piece play over structural damage. } ( { In case of } 4.Ne2 { , the practical decision is to play } 4...cxd4 { , when } 5.Nxd4 { transposes back to 4.Nf3 lines. } ) cxd4! 
5. Nxd4 Nc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
6. c4 { White confronts the black centre and hopes to get the initiative. The line is important because it can also arise from the 4.c4 move-order. } e6 { Black's position is solid and not so easy to shake. } 
7. Nc3 Bc5 ( { We force White to make some concession. You could also consider } 7...Bb4 { , pinning the white knight. This has been played by some strong players, but I like } ) ( 7...Bc5 { more. } )
8. Nxc6 { However, never take the bait with . It is always dangerous with the king in the centre when everything opens up. After 8.cxd5 exd5 9.Bb5+ , the computer claims that White is already winning. } ( 8.Nb3 Bb4 { is good for Black. } ) bxc6 { Now, d5 is well protected. } 
9. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4g7]} { The attack on g7 would be annoying if we couldn't sacrifice the pawn! } Ne7! 
10. Qxg7 Ng6 ( { There is no reason to give a second pawn, although } 10...Rg8 11.Qxh7 Rb8 { gives good compensation. } ) 
11. Be2 ( 11.cxd5 Qb6 { with an attack on f2 seems fine, and otherwise Black can also just take back on d5. } ) Bf8 
12. Qf6 Be7 
13. Qf3 ( 13.Qg7 { invites a repetition after . Instead, Black can also try } 13...d4 14.Ne4 Qa5+ { followed by ...Qxe5 with an interesting ending. } ) d4 
14. Ne4 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5e5,Ga5e1][%csl Ge5]} { Black wins the e5-pawn and restores material equality. This has been played in a bunch of email games. The position is balanced, but pretty unclear. There's lots to play for in an over the board game. } 
