4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5]} ( { With this move, White secures the centre and builds a strong foundation. This line is probably somewhat underestimated. For some reason, most white players prefer piece play and more forcing lines when confronted with 3...c5!?. Playing positionally with } 4.c3 { definitely has its merits, though. If Black answers } 4...e6 { , a well-known position from the French is on the board - but with a tempo more for White!

Of course, we have no intention of playing that way. On the contrary, Black hopes to exploit the fact that the c8-h3 diagonal is not closed yet, which means it's possible to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. You have to be a little careful, though, because the bishop might become a target. } ) Nc6 
5. h3 ( { For now we leave the bishop on c8. On f5 it might be vulnerable, and we dream of - or kind of expect - that White will play the natural } 5.Nf3 { , when we can go } 5...Bg4 { , pinning the knight and putting extra pressure on d4 that way.

In this position, White has tried several moves. 5.Nf3 is just one of them! } ) { This prevents ...Bg4, but doesn't do anything good for White. } Bf5 {[%mdl 32768]} 
6. Nf3 e6 
7. Bd3 ( 7.Be2 { is probably too quiet. After } 7...cxd4 8.cxd4 Bb4+! 9.Nc3 Nge7 10.O-O O-O { Black has managed to get all pieces out and has castled with a fine position. } ) Bxd3 { Positionally, it is always a small victory for Black to exchange the light-squared bishops, because White's pawns are on the dark squares so the c1-bishop risks becoming really bad. } 
8. Qxd3 Rc8 { Threatening ...cxd4. } 
9. O-O ( { Losing a tempo with } 9.Qd1 { is probably better, but Black has a positional edge after } 9...cxd4 10.cxd4 Nge7 { followed by ...Nf5. } ) cxd4 
10. cxd4 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gb4c2][%csl Ga1]} { The point. White is forced to enter an unpleasant ending. } 
11. Qb5+ Qd7 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7b5][%csl Ga1]} { Black is better. } 
