1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 c5 
4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5]} ( { With this move, White secures the centre and builds a strong foundation. This line is probably somewhat underestimated. For some reason, most white players prefer piece play and more forcing lines when confronted with 3...c5!?. Playing positionally with } 4.c3 { definitely has its merits, though. If Black answers } 4...e6 { , a well-known position from the French is on the board - but with a tempo more for White!

Of course, we have no intention of playing that way. On the contrary, Black hopes to exploit the fact that the c8-h3 diagonal is not closed yet, which means it's possible to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. You have to be a little careful, though, because the bishop might become a target. } ) Nc6 
5. Nf3 ( { For now we leave the bishop on c8. On f5 it might be vulnerable, and we dream of - or kind of expect - that White will play the natural } 5.Nf3 { , when we can go } 5...Bg4 { , pinning the knight and putting extra pressure on d4 that way.

In this position, White has tried several moves. 5.Nf3 is just one of them! } ) cxd4 { It makes sense to clarify the situation in the centre before we play ...Bg4. } 
6. cxd4 Bg4! { Mission accomplished. } 
7. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gg4f3][%csl Gf3]} { White makes sure that it will be possible to recapture on f3 with a knight. The d4-pawn can't be taken because of Qa4+. } e6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
8. Be2 ( 8.h3 Bh5 { doesn't change anything. } ) Bb4! { A nice way to get the pieces out. Black lacks space so some simplification makes everything easier. } 
9. O-O Bxd2! { This is somewhat unusual. Black just gives away a good bishop for a passive knight. The justification is that the black pieces lack squares. For instance, the knight and bishop can't both be on the safe e7-spot. } ( { The most played } 9...Nge7 { can be met with } 10.h3 Bh5 11.Nb3 O-O 12.a3 Ba5 13.g4 Bg6 14.Be3 { and White's extra space might count for something, although the position is pretty unclear. Taking on d2 is much simpler! } ) 
10. Qxd2 { Forced in order not to lose the d4-pawn. } Nge7= { Black is solid and sound! } 
11. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2][%csl Gd4]} { Preparing Bb2 to protect d4 and connect the rooks. } Qa5! {[%cal Ga5d2]} { A very precise move that has to be played now, before White consolidates. As is often the case, Black would love to go into an ending where White's extra space could turn out to be a disadvantage because it leaves a lot of weak squares behind the pawns. } 
12. Qxa5 ( 12.Qb2 Nf5 { is good for Black. } ) Nxa5 
13. Bb2 Rc8 
14. Rac1 Nac6 
