5. Qg4 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg4g7][%csl Gg7]} { An aggressive queen sortie. By attacking the g7-pawn, White obviously wants to prevent Black from directly playing ...Bxc5. The downside is that the queen itself is exposed. } h5! {[%csl Gg4]} { Where should the queen go? } 
6. Qf4 { Probably the best square. White allows ...Bxc5 and claims that the move ...h5 will turn out to be a major weakening of Black's kingside. Who is right? We will soon find out. } Bxc5 
7. Bd3 {[%cal Gf7f6][%csl Ge5]} { The pawn on e5 cramps Black's position and takes the f6-square away from the knight. It goes without saying that we would love to get rid of this pawn. The remedy is the confrontational move ...f6. The timing is important, though. } Nc6 ( { The immediate } 7...f6!? { could be considered. } ) 
8. Nf3 f6! {[%csl Ge5]} { Now the fight for e5 starts. } 
9. Qg3 {[%cal Gg3g7]} ( 9.exf6 gxf6 { is fine for Black. The check on g6 is nothing. We just move the king to f8. } ) Qc7 {[%cal Gc7g7][%csl Ge5]} { Protecting g7 and increasing the pressure on e5. } 
10. O-O g5! { A nice move. The white queen starts to feel a little claustrophobic. } ( 10...fxe5 11.c4! { is risky for Black. } ) 
11. exf6 { More or less forced. } Qxg3 {[%mdl 32768]} 
12. hxg3 g4 
13. Nh4 Nxf6 {[%cal Ge8f7,Gc8d7,Ga7a6]} { Black is fine in the ending. } 
