5. Bd3 { A tricky move. } Nd7! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gd7c5]} { Black wants to take on c5 with the knight, hitting the bishop on d3. } ( { The obvious move } 5...Bxc5 { is met by } 6.Qg4! { , hitting g7. We'll see this idea in other lines as well. In this case, it's particularly strong, as the following example from a blitz game demonstrates: } 6...Ne7 7.b4! Bb6 8.Nf3 Ng6 9.h4! { Very direct play. } 9...Qc7 10.Bb2 Nc6 11.h5 Ncxe5 12.Nxe5 Nxe5 13.Qxg7 Nxd3+ 14.cxd3 Rf8 15.O-O { and White is much better. } ) 
6. Nf3 Nxc5 {[%cal Gc5d3][%csl Gd3]} 
7. O-O ( 7.Be2 { loses time. Black is fine after } 7...Ne7 8.O-O Nc6 { . } ) Ne7 { We can leave the bishop on d3 for the time being. } 
8. Nc3 Nxd3 ( { Now is a good time to take it. } 8...Nc6 { is the most played move, but White has many options, and I am not sure that the knight belongs on c6. } ) 
9. Qxd3 Bd7 
10. Bd2 Ng6 { Black had the bishops and a sound position in Andriasian-Epishin, 2019. } 
