[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "9) Advance Variation: 4.dxc5"]
[Black "Advance 4.dxc5 with 5.a3, 6.Qg4 #7"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B12"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42096827"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 c5 
4. dxc5 { Clearly the most played move and also the critical. } e6! {[%cal Gf8c5]} ( { This is the right response. Black wants to take the pawn back with ...Bxc5. Playing } 4...e6 { offends many Caro-Kann players because it leaves the c8-bishop behind the pawn and is more French than Caro-Kann! This is true, but let me briefly tell you why it is necessary. } ) ( 4...Nc6 { has been tried a lot. Unfortunately, it doesn't work. Simply protecting the e5-pawn with } 5.f4 { is much better for White. Also, the old line } { 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.c3 e6 7.Be3 is just good for White.

The result is that many hardcore Caro-Kann players have abandoned the 3...c5 line and gone for the more positional 3...Bf5 instead. In this course I aim to rehabilitate 3...c5! } { Let's return to the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.dxc5 e6! White plays a French with an extra move, you can claim. It could arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.e5 c5 4.dxc5 , and then it would be Black to move.

Yes, that is all true, but in the pure French, White would never take on c5! In the French, everybody plays the much stronger 4.c3 , just securing the centre, so in our version White has already taken on c5. This is important. I guess you can say that White has an extra move, but they have used that move to start with an inferior plan!

OK, all philosophy aside, let's be more concrete. There is a reason this is the modern mainline. With 4.dxc5, White manages to put pressure on Black's position and often gets a dangerous initiative. I will show that with well-timed and precise counterstrikes, Black is very much alive and kicking, and can fight for the full point! Many of the positions are double-edged, but that is exactly what we strive for, and theoretically Black is doing fine.

I have to warn you! There are many complicated lines, and this chapter is the longest and most difficult in the whole course. What is important, when you start employing this repertoire in your own games, is that you know some of the critical lines by heart - at least the beginning of these lines! - and that you have a feel for White's plans and how to interfere with them. You don't need to remember everything. Nobody remembers everything, at least not a while after they've studied an opening! I am sure the bravery of entering such sharp positions will be rewarded. } ) 
5. a3 { This little move is the current mainline. It is a multi-functional move that on the one hand makes sure that the bishop can be on d3 without ever being bothered by ...Nb4, and on the other hand prepares active operations with b4. White has tried many other set-ups without coming up with something concrete. } ( { Note that } 5.Nc3 Nc6 { transposes to the Advance rare lines chapter, specifically to the line [/variation/41961597/#/5/b] 4.Nc3 Nc6 5.dxc5 e6. } ) Bxc5 
6. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4g7]} { Hitting g7. } Ne7! { White's previous move, Qg4, is often seen in the French, and here too, the best reaction from Black is to sac g7 and h7! } 
7. b4 h5! ( { A cool intermediate move. The more normal } 7...Bb6 { is also playable. } ) 
8. Qd1! { This retreat is actually best. } Bb6 
9. Nf3 ( 9.Bb2 Ng6 { might transpose. } ) Ng6 $146  ( { In all games that reached this position so far, Black has played } 9...a5 { , but I am not so certain about the position that arises after } 10.Bb2 axb4 11.axb4 Rxa1 12.Bxa1 { . I guess Black is fine, it is probably just equal. Anyway, I prefer the immediate 9...Ng6, which leads to more fighting positions! } ) 
10. Bb2 Nc6 
11. c4 { This is a typical break, but here the back up isn't ready. } Bc7 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Ge5]} { Attacking e5. } 
12. Nc3 O-O 
13.-- ( { Black is better. A sample line goes } 13.cxd5 Ncxe5 14.Be2 exd5 15.Nxd5 Nxf3+ 16.Bxf3 Re8+ { A very annoying check! } 17.Ne3 Nh4! { and Black is much better. } )
