5. a3 { This little move is the current mainline. It is a multi-functional move that on the one hand makes sure that the bishop can be on d3 without ever being bothered by ...Nb4, and on the other hand prepares active operations with b4. White has tried many other set-ups without coming up with something concrete. } ( { Note that } 5.Nc3 Nc6 { transposes to the Advance rare lines chapter, specifically to the line [/variation/41961597/#/5/b] 4.Nc3 Nc6 5.dxc5 e6. } ) Bxc5 
6. b4!? { A very direct and sharp continuation. } ( 6.Nf3 { is a popular move, but after } 6...f6! { it will transpose to the mainline because White has nothing better than } 7.b4 Be7 { . } ) Be7! {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This retreat is perhaps counter-intuitive. The natural move would be } 6...Bb6 { , as on e7 the bishop seems to be in the way. Isn't the knight supposed to go there?

All this is true, but we need to go deeper! Black's main plan is to confront the annoying e5-pawn with ...f6. After some exchanges on e5, we must assume that a white piece - bishop or knight - is occupying this key square. Then the idea is to play ...Bf6 and keep fighting for e5 and never give White time to create a stable outpost. That is why } ) ( 6...Be7 { is stronger than } ) ( 6...Bb6! ) 
7. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7]} { A very concrete move. With the bishop on e7, Black can't play the standard pawn sacrifice ...Ne7 and is forced to protect g7. } g6 ( { The most natural. It weakens the dark squares on the kingside which so far doesn't seem catastrophic. } 7...Kf8 { also seems playable, but I prefer not to lose the right to castle. } ) 
8. Nf3 ( { Sometimes White starts with } 8.Bd3 { , but after } 8...a5 9.b5 Nd7 10.Nf3 { we are back in the mainline. } ) a5! {[%cal Ga5b4]} { The attack on b4 forces White to compromise the structure. } 
9. b5 {[%csl Gc5]} { Almost exclusively played - bxa5 is just too ugly - but now Black has the nice c5-square. That was the positional idea behind the strike with ...a5. } Nd7 
10. Bd3 h5! ( { Black needs to solve some issues on the kingside as well. } 10...Nc5 { could be tried, but we are not really threatening to take on d3. I prefer to leave the knight on d7, from where it also attacks the e5-pawn. } ) 
11. Qg3 { This invites the following move. } h4 
12. Qf4 ( { The best square. After } 12.Qg4 Qc7 { , the e5-pawn is weak, and the queen can be hit again with ...Nh6. } ) b6 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc8b7,Ga8c8,Gg8h6][%csl Ge8]} { Black is fine in a positionally demanding position. I like the c5-square and I also like the possibility to play ...Nh6. The light-squared bishop can go to b7 and the rook to c8. The king can remain where it is for a long time, because the position is so closed. } 
