OK, all philosophy aside, let's be more concrete. There is a reason this is the modern mainline. With 4.dxc5, White manages to put pressure on Black's position and often gets a dangerous initiative. I will show that with well-timed and precise counterstrikes, Black is very much alive and kicking, and can fight for the full point! Many of the positions are double-edged, but that is exactly what we strive for, and theoretically Black is doing fine.

I have to warn you! There are many complicated lines, and this chapter is the longest and most difficult in the whole course. What is important, when you start employing this repertoire in your own games, is that you know some of the critical lines by heart - at least the beginning of these lines! - and that you have a feel for White's plans and how to interfere with them. You don't need to remember everything. Nobody remembers everything, at least not a while after they've studied an opening! I am sure the bravery of entering such sharp positions will be rewarded. } ) 
5. a3 { This little move is the current mainline. It is a multi-functional move that on the one hand makes sure that the bishop can be on d3 without ever being bothered by ...Nb4, and on the other hand prepares active operations with b4. White has tried many other set-ups without coming up with something concrete. } ( { Note that } 5.Nc3 Nc6 { transposes to the Advance rare lines chapter, specifically to the line [/variation/41961597/#/5/b] 4.Nc3 Nc6 5.dxc5 e6. } ) Bxc5 
6. b4!? { A very direct and sharp continuation. } ( 6.Nf3 { is a popular move, but after } 6...f6! { it will transpose to the mainline because White has nothing better than } 7.b4 Be7 { . } ) Be7! ( { This retreat is perhaps counter-intuitive. The natural move would be } 6...Bb6 { , as on e7 the bishop seems to be in the way. Isn't the knight supposed to go there?

All this is true, but we need to go deeper! Black's main plan is to confront the annoying e5-pawn with ...f6. After some exchanges on e5, we must assume that a white piece - bishop or knight - is occupying this key square. Then the idea is to play ...Bf6 and keep fighting for e5 and never give White time to create a stable outpost. That is why } ) ( 6...Be7 { is stronger than } ) ( 6...Bb6! ) 
7. Nf3 ( 7.Bb2 f6 { transposes. White doesn't have anything better than } 8.Nf3 { . } ) f6! {[%csl Ge5]} ( { Black starts the fight for e5 at once. Instead, after } 7...a5 8.b5 Nd7 { White has scored well with } 9.c4 { . } ) 
8. Bb2 a5! { A key move that tries to weaken the white pawn structure and conquer the c5-square. } 
9. b5 ( 9.bxa5 { is anti-positional. It ruins the queenside and Black still gets the c5-square. } 9...Nc6 10.Nbd2 Nh6 { , like in the mainline, looks good for Black. } ) Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5][%csl Ge5]} { The fight is primarily for the e5-square, but the knight has a great spot available on c5. } 
10. Nbd2 { This is met by the same idea. } Nh6! {[%mdl 32768]} 
11. Bd3 Nf7 {[%csl Ge5]} { White is forced to take on f6, which can be considered a small victory for Black. } 
12. exf6 Bxf6 
13. Bxf6 Qxf6 
14. c4 { White has to play actively. Otherwise, Black is just very comfortable with the knight coming to c5. } Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d3]} { With tempo. } 
15. Bc2 b6! { Black plays some strong positional moves instead of just castling. } 
16. cxd5 ( 16.O-O a4! { transposes after } 17.cxd5 exd5 { . } ) exd5 
17. O-O a4! {[%csl Gb3]} { This prevents Nb3. Black is not afraid of a check on the e-file. } 
18. Re1+ ( 18.Qb1 h6 19.Re1+ Be6 { is a transposition. } ) Be6 
19. Nf1 ( { Better is } 19.Qb1 h6 20.Bh7!? { , which prevents short castling! } { 20.Qb4 O-O is fine for Black. } { However, Black can answer } 20...O-O-O !? { or } { 20...g5 , with a complicated fight where Black seems to be doing absolutely fine. } ) O-O { Black has a promising position. See Haubro-Jacobsen [/variation/42271881/#/19/b], Denmark 2022 in the Model Games section. } 
