[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "Exchange Variation: Overview"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: Introduction"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41961855"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 { The Exchange variation is a very popular choice at all levels. The pawn structure is defined and an interesting maneuvering game can begin. } 
4. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3f5,Gd1g4][%csl Gc8]} { White has several options, but this bishop move is surely the most natural. It prevents ...Bf5, which makes it hard for Black to get the light-squared bishop out, and White's bishop stands well on d3. } ( { The sharp } 4.c4 { is covered in the Panov chapters. In that case White strives for the initiative and doesn't mind playing with an isolated d-pawn. } ) ( 4.Bf4 { might look a little strange, but it is a quite important line, because it often occurs via the London system. Consider @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 cxd4 4.exd4 and voila! So if you are a Caro-Kann player, it is easy to get a good game against the London without preparing anything special.

The London transposition is perhaps the most clean-cut, but if you play the Queen's Gambit with Black there are other well-known transpositions, like the Colle: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 c5 4.c3 cxd4 5.exd4 . Here we have the typical Caro-Kann pawn structure, but the knight is already on f6, so it is not totally identical to the lines in this Caro-Kann repertoire. Still, knowing this structure (which is also very common with colours reversed in the Queen's Gambit Declined Exchange Variation and is called the Carlsbad) could benefit your game in general. I think it is one of the most important pawn formations. The best player in this structure - with either colour! - is by far Magnus Carlsen. It could pay off to study some of his games. } ) ( { The modest } 4.c3 { shouldn't trouble us, but don't underestimate this move! After all, the pawn structure is well known from the so-called Carlsbad structure in the exchange variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. Here the colours are reversed, of course, but the play is still very strategically complicated. } ) ( { Finally, there is } 4.Nf3 { , in which case White is flirting with moves like Ne5 and Bb5. } ) Nc6 {[%csl Gd4]} 
5. c3 {[%cal Gc1f4]} { White intends Bf4 next. } Qc7! {[%csl Gf4]} ( { So we prevent it! The old mainline goes } 5...Nf6 6.Bf4 Bg4 7.Qb3 Qd7 8.Nd2 e6 9.Ngf3 Bd6! 10.Bxd6 Qxd6 11.O-O O-O { and Black is solid. White has a very straightforward plan with } 12.Rae1 { or } { 12.Rfe1 , in both cases planning Ne5. I think Black should be ok, but White's play is almost too easy. This line has been covered on Chessable from Black's perspective by both Sielecki and L'Ami. } ) ( { I think that } 5...Qc7! { leads to much more interesting play and gives Black more winning chances, so we will go for that. After all, this is my big ambition with this course: to give Black some excellent starting points, from where it is possible to outplay the opponent. } ) 
*

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "Exchange Variation: Overview"]
[Black "Sethuraman, SP. vs. Erdogmus, Yagiz Kaan, Sharjah 2024"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B13"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42271883"]

1. e4 c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. Bd3 { The Exchange variation has always been a popular choice for White against the Caro-Kann. It is very easy to play. } Nc6 
5. c3 Qc7 {[%csl Gf4]} 
6. h3 { The best setup for White according to modern opening theory. } e6!? {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7]} { Black goes for a flexible piece formation with ...Bd6 and ...Nge7. Later the c8-bishop might play a role. We will see! } 
7. Nf3 Bd6 
8. O-O Nge7 
9. Re1 O-O 
10. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3,Gc3c4]} { Preparing to develop the bishop to b2 or a3. It could also go to e3, but there it would be rather passive. An additional point of b3 is that it prepares to play c4 and then take back with the pawn. } Ng6!? {[%csl Gf4]} { Black improves the knight. From g6 it can jump to f4. } ( { In the theory section [/variation/42135111/#/10/b] recommend } 10...Rd8 { as our main move. } ) 
11. Ba3 {[%csl Gd6]} ( { Eliminating Black's strong bishop. Perhaps stronger is } 11.c4 { , but after the precise } 11...Bb4! 12.Bd2 Bxd2 13.Qxd2 dxc4 14.bxc4 Rd8 { Black has some pressure against the hanging pawns. } ) Bd7 ( { Again } 11...Rd8 { is a good alternative. } ) 
12. Bxd6 Qxd6 
13. Nbd2 Rac8 {[%cal Gg6f4][%csl Gc3]} { Black can be satisfied with the outcome of the opening. The position is balanced, yet full of potential. From c8 the rook eyes the weak white c-pawn, the black knight can jump to f4 and attack White's bishop, and finally the black centre can be mobilized with ...f6 and ...e5, which will also free the d7-bishop. } 
14. Nf1 ( { Probably better was } 14.Rc1 { . } ) Nf4 
15. Bc2 f6! {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd7e8,Ge8h5]} { This prepares the attractive break with ...e5, but also creates a new route to liberate the d7-bishop. } 
16. Ne3 Be8 {[%cal Ge8g6,Gg6h5]} { It is going to g6 or h5. } 
17. h4?! { This is too weakening. White would like to kick the black knight away with g3 and makes sure that the h3-pawn doesn't hang. However, it turns out that the cure is much worse than the disease! } Bh5 {[%cal Gh5d1]} { An unpleasant pin. White feels obliged to break it, although this weakens the kingside even more. } 
18. g4 Bg6 
19. Bxg6 hxg6 { Black is much better now. } 
20. Ng2 Nh3+ 
21. Kf1 e5 { With a strong initiative. } 
22. Ng1 Nxg1 
23. Kxg1 e4 { Taking more space. } 
24. f4 { Trying to close the kingside. } b5 
25. b4 Nd8 
26. Qb3 f5 
27. a4 ( { Also hopeless is } 27.g5 Ne6 28.Rf1 Rc4 { followed by ...Rfc8. } ) Ne6! {[%csl Gf4]} { The kingside matters more than the rest of the board. } 
28. axb5 Nxf4 
29. Ra6 ( 29.Nxf4 Qxf4 30.Qxd5+ Kh7 { doesn't help. White's king is completely naked. } ) Nh3+ ( { Perhaps even stronger was } 29...Qb8 { . } ) 
30. Kh1 Qg3 
31. Re3 Qxg4 
32. Qxd5+ Kh7 
33. Ra2 f4! { Black is completely winning. The young Turkish player finds the most effective way to prove it. } 
34. Qxe4 ( { Pinning. Or } 34.Rxe4 Rxc3 { . } ) Rce8! 
35. Qxe8 Rxe8 
36. Rxe8 f3 {[%cal Gg4g1]} { The point. The white knight can't move due to mate on g1. Black wins material, and soon after he wins the game. } 
37. Rf8 Qg3!? 
38. d5 Nf2+! 
39. Rxf2 ( 39.Kg1 Qxg2 { . } ) Qxf2 
40. Nf4 Qe1+ 
41. Kh2 f2 
42. Nh3 f1=N+ 
43. Kg2 Qg3+ 
44. Kxf1 Qxh3+ 
45. Ke2 Qxc3 
46. Rf4 Qe5+ 
47. Kf3 Qxd5+ 
48. Kg3 Qxb5 
49. Rg4 Kh6 
0-1

