[ECO "B13"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42134103"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4]} { White builds the classical pawn structure. This takes time and doesn't threaten anything, so we have the time to get our bishop out. } Bf5! ( { An original solution. Of course it is also possible just to go } 4...Nc6 { , which might transpose to the 4.Bd3 mainline. } ) 
5. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7]} ( { Attacking the b7-pawn. This is the only active try. } 5.Bf4 { transposes to the line [/variation/41961875/#/5/w] 4.Bf4, while } ) ( 5.Bd3 Bxd3 6.Qxd3 e6 { gives Black easy play. } ) Qd7 
6. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5]} { Intending Ne5. } e6! {[%mdl 32768]} ( { A precise reaction. We are not afraid of ghosts. } 6...Nc6 7.Nh4! { has scored well for White. } ) 
7. Ne5 Qc8 { Black is under some pressure, but the main thing is that we got our light-squared bishop out! Next, we can challenge the white knight on e5. White can try several moves and hope to keep the initiative going. Black's position is very firm, though, and can withstand everything! } 
8. Bb5+ Nc6 
