1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. Bf4 { This position often comes from the London ( @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 cxd4 4.exd4 ), which makes it extra important. } Nc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
5. c3 ( { The standard construction of the centre. } 5.Nf3 { would transpose to 4.Nf3, which we'll discuss in the next chapter [/course/261638/15]. } ) Bf5! { The bishop goes to a very sympathetic spot. } 
6. Bd3 Bxd3 
7. Qxd3 { Positionally speaking, it is nice for Black to exchange the light-squared bishops, because it removes a lot of the pressure on Black's position. } e6 
8. Nf3 Bd6 { Going for the complete removal of bishops from the board! This is the simple and sound solution. Black can also keep the bishops which might be a better winning try. I will give it as an alternative. } 
9. Bxd6 Qxd6 
10. O-O Nf6 
11. Nbd2 O-O 
12. Rfe1 {[%cal Gf3e5]} { White wants to play Ne5 with a grip on the centre. Black has to be ready to meet this, otherwise the position can quickly become unpleasant. } Qc7! ( { A great prophylactic move. Black intends to capture on e5 if White plays Ne5, when dxe5 no longer wins a piece. } 12...Nd7 { is a good alternative. } ) 
13. Ne5 { It is hard to come up with another good plan. White could also try to regroup with Nb3 intending Qe2 and Nc1-d3. It takes a lot of time, and if Black just puts the knight on d7 so it controls the important c5-square there is a good chance that Black can take over with the minority attack: ...a5, ...b5 and finally ...b4. } Nxe5! { The point of Black's previous move. } 
14. dxe5 ( 14.Rxe5 { has never been played. An interesting way to meet it is the computer suggestion } 14...a5!? ) ( 14.a4 Ra6 { when it is hard for both sides to do anything, but in the long run we can try to get the break ...b5 in. } ) Nd7 
15. Nf3 h6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4][%csl Gc4]} { The position is balanced. Black will try to play on the queenside with the standard ...b5-b4 plan or by occupying the c4-square. In general we don't mind to exchnage some pieces, even the queens, if we can keep some potential on the queenside. } 
*

