5. c3 ( { The standard construction of the centre. } 5.Nf3 { would transpose to 4.Nf3, which we'll discuss in the next chapter [/course/261638/15]. } ) Bf5! { The bishop goes to a very sympathetic spot. } 
6. Nf3 ( 6.Qb3 Qd7 { will transpose to the line [/variation/41961890/#/7/b] 6.Nf3 after } 7.Nf3 { or first } { 7.Nd2 and then Ngf3. } ) ( 6.Nd2 e6 7.Ngf3 { is another transposition to 6.Nf3. } ) e6 
7. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7]} Qd7 ( 7...Bd6 8.Qxb7 Bxf4 9.Qxc6+ Kf8 { is a pawn sacrifice that the computers approve of. Play might continue } 10.Nbd2 Rb8 11.Nb3 g6 { followed by ...Kg7 with an interesting game ahead. } ) ( { There really is no need to sacrifice the b7-pawn, so I have chosen the solid } 7...Qd7 { as our mainline. } ) 
8. Nbd2 { White prioritizes harmonic development. More aggressive approaches actually makes black's play pretty easy. } Nge7 ( { Planning Ng6. } 8...f6!? { , intending ...g5 and ...h5, is a sharp alternative. } ) 
9. h3 {[%cal Gf4h2]} { Making a retreat for the bishop. This motif just pops up all the time for both sides in these lines. } Ng6 
