1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. Nf3 { An important position for the practical player. Although the knight on f3 allows Black to play Bg4, what we in fact have is a strategically demanding line of the Queen's Gambit Declined with colours reversed. } Nc6 
5. Ne5!? {[%cal Gf1b5][%csl Gc6]} { Very active looking. The idea is to follow up with Bb5. } e6! {[%mdl 32768]} { Safe and sound. We don't mind to get the passive Bc8 exchanged for the strong white knight. } 
6. c3 Bd6 
7. f4 {[%csl Ge5]} { This is a completely different way of playing. White secures the knight and the extra space for now. In the long run Black will kick the knight away with f6 and the move f4 has left a lot of holes in White's position, things we hope to exploit. } Nge7 
8. Bd3 O-O 
9. O-O f6! { Here it comes. } 
10. Qh5 {[%csl Gh7]} ( { White needs to attack. } 10.Nf3 Bd7 $146 { is fine for Black. } ) Nf5 
11. g4 ( { There is no way back. } 11.Bxf5 exf5 12.Nd3 Re8 { is positionally terrible for White with the weak square on e4 and bad dark-squared bishop. } ) fxe5 ( 11...Nh6 { is also fine. } ) 
12. fxe5 ( 12.gxf5 e4 { wins for Black. } ) Nxe5! 
13. dxe5 Bc5+ 
14. Kh1 g6! 
15. Qh3 Nh4 $146  ( 15...Qh4 { is playable as well } ) 
16. Rxf8+ Qxf8 
17. Nd2 Qf2 
18.-- ( { Black has the initiative. A sample line goes } 18.Qg3 Bd7 19.Nb3 Bc6 20.Nxc5 Qxc5 21.Qxh4 d4+ 22.Kg1 dxc3+ 23.Qf2 Qd5 { and Black wins. White should probably have exchanged the queens, but Black still has good play regardless. } )
