1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. Bd3 {[%csl Gc8]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4][%csl Rd4]} 
5. c3 Qc7 {[%cal Rc1f4][%csl Rf4]} { Preventing Bf4. } 
6. Ne2 {[%cal Gc1f4]} { This used to be the mainline. } e6!? {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7]} { Also here this modern idea is really interesting. Compared to the new mainline 6.h3, White now has the chance to exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 
7. Bf4 Bd6 
8. Bxd6 Qxd6 { At first sight it looks pleasant for White, but Black is very flexible. } 
9. O-O Nge7 {[%cal Gf7f6][%csl Ge5]} { The right square. Black wants to play ...f6 and take control over the important e5-square. } 
10. Nd2 O-O 
11. f4 {[%csl Ge5]} ( { White takes space and makes sure that Black won't get ...f6 and ...e5 in. } 11.Nf3 f6 { has scored well for Black. If } 12.Qc2 { then just } 12...g6 { . Sooner or later Black will push ...e5 with good play. } ) Bd7 
12. Nf3 f6 {[%csl Gh7]} { The position is very complicated. White can hit the h7-pawn and try to inflict some damage. } 
13. Qc2 g6 
14. Rae1 Rae8 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gd8f7,Ge7c6,Ge6e5]} { Both sides are fully developed, which basically means that there are no more easy moves to make! Now you must come up with some kind of a plan. Black can regroup the knights with ...Nc6-d8-f7 and ...Ne7-c6 and try to get ...e5 in. The position is playable for sure, although objectively White is perhaps slightly better. } 
*

