[Black "Exchange 4.Bd3 with 6.Na3 #1"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42134983"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. Bd3 {[%csl Gc8]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 
5. c3 Qc7 {[%csl Gf4]} { Preventing Bf4. } 
6. Na3 { A well-known manoeuvre from the QGD. } a6 {[%mdl 32768]} { We don't want to allow Nb5 and Bf4. } 
7. Nc2 e6 
8. Nf3 Bd6 
9. O-O Nge7 { Black again goes for this very flexible set-up. } 
10. Re1 O-O! ( { I proposed } 10...Bd7 { in my book, but this is stronger. } ) 
11. Bxh7+ { Sacrifices like this followed by Ng5+ and Qh5 are always nerve-wracking. If we keep our cool for a moment, it is easy to see that it doesn't work! } Kxh7 
12. Ng5+ Kg6! 
13. Qg4 {[%csl Gg6]} { It surely looks dangerous to put it mildly. Now watch this: } f5 
14. Qh3 Bd7 $146  {[%cal Gf8h8][%csl Gh3]} { The beginning of the refutation. } 
15. Qh7+ ( 15.Nxe6 Bxe6 16.Rxe6+ Kf7 { and the attack is over. } ) Kf6 
16. Qh5 ( { The only move. } 16.Qh4 { is answered by } 16...Rh8! ) g6! ( { Not } 16...Rh8?? 17.Qf7# { . } ) 
17. Nh7+ ( 17.Qh7 f4! { followed by ...Nf5. } ) Kf7 
18. Ng5+ Ke8! { No draw. } 
19. Qh6 Nd8 
20.-- ( { Black covers everything and White doesn't have enough for the piece. A sample line goes } 20.Nh7 Rg8 21.Nf6+ Kf7 22.Nxg8 Kxg8 { when our king is finally safe and White's queen can be evicted next with ...Nf7. } )
*

