[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "Panov Variation: Overview"]
[Black "Panov Variation: Introduction"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41962029"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 ( 2.c4 { is very popular at the club level. White plays a kind of Panov, but without the move d4. Omitting that move speeds everything up, and very soon White will get some extra possibilities. } 2...d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.cxd5 Nf6 { This is the real starting position of the Pseudo-Panov variation. White can accept playing with an isolated d-pawn by going } 5.Nc3 { , but giving a check with either the bishop ( } { 5.Bb5+ ) or with the queen ( 5.Qa4+ ) leads to more tricky positions. We don't need to fear these moves, however. To the contrary: if White tries to get more out of the opening than there is, it may backfire! In all lines Black is in good shape, but you do need to know what to do. } ) d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c4 ( { This is one of White's most direct approaches against the Caro-Kann. Named after the imaginative Russian player Vasily Panov, the move } 4.c4 { appeals to white players who strive for the initiative and like to play with active pieces. Often it leads to strategically interesting positions, where White has an isolated d-pawn. It was a favourite of the legendary Soviet World Champion Mikhail Botvinnik and also a dangerous weapon in the hands of attacking players like Judit Polgar. In recent years the popularity of the Panov has faded somewhat because Black has found some really good set-ups. } ) Nf6 
5. Nc3 Nc6! { The best move in my opinion. It leaves all options open depending on how White reacts. } ( 5...e6 6.Nf3 Bb4 { was Karpov's response. Play is quite similar to the Nimzo Indian. Black could also go for the solid 6...Be7. In all cases typical IQP-positions arises, such as after } 7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qc2 { with a complicated fight, where White has some initiative. } ) ( 5...g6 { Is a Grunfeld style way of playing. Here the mainline goes } 6.Qb3 Bg7 7.cxd5 O-O 8.Be2 Nbd7 9.Bf3 Nb6 10.Nge2 { . White has kept the extra pawn, but Black has decent compensation. } ) ( { What I really like about } 5...Nc6 { is that we don't clarify the situation prematurely. Let's first see what White intends! Another advantage is that Black can opt for some really demanding middlegames, where we hopefully can outplay our opponents. White basically has two responses: the positional } 6.Nf3 { and the sharp . } ) 
6. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6][%csl Gd5]} { Very aggressive and forceful. White puts pressure on the d5-pawn. } ( 6.Nf3 a6! { is a completely new and very cunning idea. Black makes an intelligent waiting move and is ready to face any move from White. This leads to very interesting positions. } { 6...Bg4 This classical response was my recommended reply against 6.Nf3 in my Caro-Kann books. It leads more or less by force to an equal ending after 7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+ Ke7 13.Qxb5 Even the surprising piece sacrifice 13.Qc5+ Nd6 14.Nxd5+ exd5 15.O-O is fully playable for White. 13...Qd7 14.Nxd5+ Qxd5 15.Qxd5 exd5 . I have managed to win this ending against a good opponent, but objectively Black should be happy with a draw. That is why I have switched to 6...a6! }) Be6! {[%csl Gd5]} { Another surprise. We just protect d5 in a very unusual way. } ( 6...dxc4 { has been the main theoretical move and also the mainline in my books. White should continue actively by sacrificing the d-pawn with } 7.Bxc4 { . Play becomes really sharp. Black is ok according to deep analysis, but why give White what they want? } ) ( 6...Be6 { is a fresh move that leads to rather original positions, that are difficult to play for both sides. So with some good preparation Black's winning chances might increase dramatically! } ) 
*

