8. Nc3 e5! {[%csl Gc5,Gd4]} { White's centre is under fire. The move is not really a pawn sacrifice, but rather it leads to some exchanges. This means that Black's position will be liberated before White can get a long-term grip. White can now either take on e5 or first exchange the knights and then take, or try to protect the d4-pawn. In all cases Black has good play. } 
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 
10. dxe5 Nxc3 
11. bxc3 Bxc5 ( 11...Qa5!? { is a good alternative. } ) 
12. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7][%csl Gd3]} { After the knights have disappeared we have a pretty equal position. White's light-squared bishop is strong, but that is about the only positive thing you can say about White. } O-O 
13. O-O Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8][%csl Rc3]} { Black has easy development. We can dream of putting pressure on the weak c-pawn. } 
14. Kh2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} { White's only active plan is to push the f-pawn. That could be really dangerous, so we better start fighting against it. } f6 { Black is fine. Now White's best is to force a draw. } 
15. Qh5 g6 ( 15...h6? { would be a big mistake due to } 16.Qg6 { . } ) ( 15...f5 { is playable, however. } 16.Qe2 Rc8 17.f4 d4! { and Black has counterplay. } ) 
16. Bxg6 hxg6 
17. Qxg6+ Kh8 {[%cal Gg6h6,Gh6g6,Gh8g8,Gg8h8]} { White has to give perpetual check. } 
