6. h3!? {[%csl Gg4]} { Preventing Bg4. } ( 6.Nc3 { would transpose to 5.Nc3 Nf6 6.Nf3, which is seen in the next chapter [/course/261638/19]. } ) a6 $146  ( { This new move solves all problems. } 6...g6 { is the natural reaction, but then } 7.c5! Bg7 8.Bb5 { intending Ne5 is annoying. } ) 
7. c5 ( { The typical Panov move. } 7.Nc3 { would again transpose to 5.Nc3 Nf6 6.Nf3 lines. } ) Ne4 ( 7...e5!? { at once also seems fine. } ) 
8. Nc3 e5! {[%csl Gc5,Gd4]} { White's centre is under fire. The move is not really a pawn sacrifice, but rather it leads to some exchanges. This means that Black's position will be liberated before White can get a long-term grip. White can now either take on e5 or first exchange the knights and then take, or try to protect the d4-pawn. In all cases Black has good play. } 
9. Be3 {[%csl Gd4]} { Secures the d4-point, but leads to mass exchanges nevertheless. } exd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 
10. Nxd4 Bxc5 
11. Nxe4 ( { The right way. Instead, } 11.Nxc6 bxc6 12.Nxe4 Bxe3! { is good for Black. } ) Bxd4! ( { Not } 11...dxe4 12.Nxc6 Qxd1+ 13.Rxd1 { and White wins a piece because of } 13...Bxe3 14.Rd8# { . } ) 
12. Bxd4 Nxd4 ( { Not } 12...dxe4 13.Bxg7 { . } ) 
13. Qxd4 dxe4 
14. Qxe4+ Be6 { The position is equal. There is a nice trap though. } 
15. Qxb7? { The pawn is poisoned. } Qa5+! { Black wins. } 
16. b4 ( { After } 16.Ke2 O-O { White won't survive for long with the king in the centre. } ) Qe5+ {[%cal Ge5e1,Ge5a1]} 
17. Kd2 Rd8+ 
18. Bd3 { White tries to save the rook on a1. } Qb2+! { But this is a killer. } 
19. Ke3 Qd4+ {[%csl Rd3]} { Game over. } 
*

