1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c4 Nf6 
5. c5 { This is a typical idea in the Panov. Here, before developing the knights, it gives Black some extra opportunities. } e5! {[%csl Gd4]} { The thematic counter. } 
6. Nc3 exd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( 6...Nc6 { would transpose to a line [/variation/41962081/#/6/b] we'll see later, but there is no reason not to try to punish White for the premature 5.c5. } ) 
7. Qxd4 Nc6 
8. Bb5 { The only move. If White is starting to back down, their opening has been a failure. } Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} { Black just prepares to castle. That would also break the pin on the c6-knight and more or less force White to take on c6. } 
9. Nf3 O-O 
10. Bxc6 bxc6 
11. Ne5 {[%csl Gc6]} ( { Attacking the c6-pawn. } 11.O-O Nd7 { is much better for Black. } ) Qe8! { Defending the pawn and at the same time setting a small trap. } 
12. O-O Bxc5! {[%csl Ge5]} 
13. Qxc5 Qxe5 
14. Qxc6 Ng4! { Black gets a decisive attack. } 
15. g3 ( 15.f4 Qd4+ 16.Kh1 Nf2+ { wins an exchange because } 17.Kg1? { leads to the well-known smothered mate: } 17...Nh3+ 18.Kh1 Qg1+ 19.Rxg1 Nf2# ) Qh5 
16. h4 Ne5! {[%cal Gc8h3][%csl Gf3]} { White is getting crushed on the light squares. } 
17. Qxd5 Bh3 
18.-- ( { Black is completely winning. A sample line goes } 18.Rd1 Bg4 19.Rf1 Bf3 20.Qb3 Qf5 21.Kh2 Bc6 { followed by ...Nf3+. } )
