[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "13) Panov Variation: Rare Lines"]
[Black "Panov 5.Nc3 with 6.Bf4 #1"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42163881"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5]} { Active development and putting pressure on d5 immediately. } ( { The early capture } 5.cxd5 { is not justified. After } 5...Nxd5 6.Nc3 Nc6 { we are back in the mainline. Black can even try to exploit White's move order and go for } { 6...g6!? . My guess is that you will never face 5.cxd5, so there is no need to learn extra lines! } ) Nc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
6. Bf4 {[%cal Gc3b5][%csl Gc7]} { A good square for the bishop. The move demands a good answer from Black! } g6! { That' s it. We have a tactical defense ready if White goes for Nb5. } ( 6...a6 7.c5 g6 { is a playable alternative, but the move ...a6 loses time and weakens the queenside. } ) 
7. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7]} e5! { Without this move we would be in trouble. } 
8. dxe5 Bb4+! { It all comes with tempo. } 
9. Bd2 ( 9.Ke2 O-O! 10.exf6 Qxf6 { gives Black a winning attack. } ) Bxd2+ 
10. Qxd2 Nxe5 
11. cxd5 { Winning the d-pawn, but the price is high. Probably too high. } O-O! ( { Not } 11...Nxd5? 12.Qxd5 { . } ) 
12. Nc3 Re8 {[%cal Ge8e1]} { The white king is the problem. Black gets great play for the pawn. } 
13. Be2 ( 13.O-O-O Bf5 { followed by ...Rc8 keeps the white king in the crossfire. } ) b5! {[%cal Gb5b4][%csl Rd5]} 
14.-- ( { Threatening ...b4 and in general just tries to get the last pieces - the bishop and the a8-rook - into play while White is more or less paralyzed. A possible line goes } 14.a3 a5 15.Nxb5 Nxd5 16.Rd1 Bb7 { and the computer claims Black is just winning. It is a waste of time to argue with it. Instead, I suggest that you analyze the position further, because it is a good training position that can teach you a lot about long-term attacking possibilities against a king stuck in the centre. } )
*

