2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 Nc6 
6. Nf3 a6! {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This is an important departure from my previous work, where I have recommended the standard move } 6...Bg4 { which, by the way, is still an excellent choice. I just feel that Black will get more interesting positions with } ) ( 6...a6! ) ( { The } 6...Bg4 { line goes } 7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+ Ke7 13.Qxb5 { The normal move. } { White can even try the spectacular piece sacrifice 13.Qc5+!? Nd6 14.Nxd5+ exd5 15.O-O with enough compensation - the engines call it 0.00! } 13...Qd7 14.Nxd5+ Qxd5 { with an equal ending. } ) ( 6...Be6 { is probably too sophisticated to be good, but be aware of the idea! I actually recommend it against the sharp 6.Bg5. Here, though, after } 7.c5 g6 8.Bb5 { White is just better. } ) 
7. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6][%csl Gd5]} { White puts pressure on the d5-pawn. } Be6! { An unusual way to defend it. In general I think ...Be6 is a good move when White has already played Bg5, otherwise I believe we should refrain from it. } 
8. Bxf6 exf6! { Maybe a little counter-intuitive, but this is the right way to recapture. It opens the path for the dark-squared bishop and usually transposes to one of the other lines if White plays Be2 or c5. } 
9. cxd5 Bxd5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gd5f3][%csl Gd4]} { Black has good play against the d-pawn. Easy developing moves like ...Be7 and ...O-O should be played first. Then ...Bxf3 often becomes a threat, removing a key defender of d4, so White probably takes on d5 and we take back with the queen and follow up by moving a rook to d8. In general everything runs smooth! } 
