3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 Nc6 
6. Nf3 a6! ( { This is an important departure from my previous work, where I have recommended the standard move } 6...Bg4 { which, by the way, is still an excellent choice. I just feel that Black will get more interesting positions with } ) ( 6...a6! ) ( { The } 6...Bg4 { line goes } 7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+ Ke7 13.Qxb5 { The normal move. } { White can even try the spectacular piece sacrifice 13.Qc5+!? Nd6 14.Nxd5+ exd5 15.O-O with enough compensation - the engines call it 0.00! } 13...Qd7 14.Nxd5+ Qxd5 { with an equal ending. } ) ( 6...Be6 { is probably too sophisticated to be good, but be aware of the idea! I actually recommend it against the sharp 6.Bg5. Here, though, after } 7.c5 g6 8.Bb5 { White is just better. } ) 
7. c5 { Very thematic. } Bg4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This is an alternative to my main suggestion } 7...g6 { . Play is quite similar, but we don't have to worry about White preventing our ...Bg4 with h3 in the future anymore. } ) 
8. Be2 g6 { This is a very sound setup. } 
9. O-O Bg7 
10. Bf4 O-O 
11. h3 Bxf3 {[%csl Rd4]} { We are always happy to give our light-squared bishop for the knight because it softens the defence of d4. } 
12. Bxf3 e6 { Securing the d5-pawn and preparing to move our f6-knight. } 
13. b4 Ne8! {[%csl Rd4]} { This shows that 10.Bf4 was slightly inaccurate. Now the d4-pawn needs protection. } 
14. Be3 Qh4 {[%csl Rd4]} { Attacking d4 one more time. } 
15. Ne2 Nc7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc7b5,Gh7h6]} 
16.-- ( { Black is very comfortable. If } 16.Qd2 { then } 16...h6 { prevents Bg5 and keeps the pressure on d4. } )
