[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "15) Panov Variation: 6.Bg5"]
[Black "Panov 6.Bg5 with 7.Bxf6"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41962182"]

1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 Nc6 
6. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6][%csl Gd5]} { This active move is clearly the most dangerous one in the Panov. White attacks the f6-knight that is crucial for the defence of the important d5-pawn. } Be6! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Ge6d5]} { A very original way of defending d5. We have seen this motif several times already in the 6.Nf3 chapter, so it shouldn't come as a big surprise. } ( 6...dxc4 { is the widely recommended move, and it was also the move I suggested in my Caro-Kann books. White can then sacrifice the d4-pawn with } 7.Bxc4 { with interesting play, or in some lines even push the pawn to d5. Black is generally ok, but 6...Be6 leads to more strategically complex positions that suit this course better.

A fun fact: when the white bishop is on g5 then ...Be6 is almost always good! If the bishop is not on g5 then ...Be6 often is dubious. } ) 
7. Bxf6 { Rarely good, but the positions can be hard to judge. } exf6! { This is the right way to recapture. We have seen this already in the Nf3 chapter, so it shouldn't come as a big surprise by now. Of course, it is tempting to recapture towards the centre with ...gxf6, but that would weaken our kingside - especially the pawn on h7 - which makes it risky to castle short. Castling long is even worse though. White will get b4 in and run through our defences.

I don't expect you to remember all the complicated lines in the Panov, but to take back on f6 with the e-pawn is something you should be able to do even in your sleep! } 
8. c5 ( 8.cxd5 Bxd5 { just helps Black get good play against the isolani. } ) g6 
9. Bb5 {[%cal Gg1e2,Gb5c6][%csl Gd4]} { Pinning the knight and preparing Nge2 when the d4-pawn is well-protected. } h5!? ( { Of course you could just go } 9...Bg7 { , but this is more creative. } ) 
10. Nge2 Bh6 {[%csl Gh6]} { The point. The bishop is fine on h6. } 
11. O-O O-O {[%cal Gf6f5]} { The position is balanced. Black will soon play ...f5 and take more space on the kingside. The bishop on e6 looks miserable, but in fact it ties everything together by defending the d5-pawn. Later it can have a bright future if we manage to push ...f4, when it breaks free from its chains. } 
