1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. c4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 Nc6 
6. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6][%csl Gd5]} { This active move is clearly the most dangerous one in the Panov. White attacks the f6-knight that is crucial for the defence of the important d5-pawn. } Be6! {[%cal Ge6d5]} { A very original way of defending d5. We have seen this motif several times already in the 6.Nf3 chapter, so it shouldn't come as a big surprise. } ( 6...dxc4 { is the widely recommended move, and it was also the move I suggested in my Caro-Kann books. White can then sacrifice the d4-pawn with } 7.Bxc4 { with interesting play, or in some lines even push the pawn to d5. Black is generally ok, but 6...Be6 leads to more strategically complex positions that suit this course better.

A fun fact: when the white bishop is on g5 then ...Be6 is almost always good! If the bishop is not on g5 then ...Be6 often is dubious. } ) 
7. Nf3 { A natural developing move. Now we could play 7...a6 and transpose to the Nf3 chapter [/variation/41962111/#/7/b], but via this move order it makes sense to go on with our own plans. } g6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gf8g7]} 
{ The aggressive } 8. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3b7][%csl Gd5]} { is well met by } Na5! {[%cal Ga5b3]} { And Black defends all critical points with tempo. } 
9. Qa3 Bg7 
10. cxd5 Nxd5 ( { Even } 10...Bxd5 { is an option. } ) 
11. Bb5+ Nc6 
12. O-O Qd6! {[%cal Gd6a3]} { Now Black is fine in the ending, so White should probably go for the following. } 
13. Qa4 Nxc3 ( { Also fine is } 13...Nb6 14.Bxc6+ Qxc6 15.Qxc6 bxc6 { . Next Black can remove the pressure on e7 by playing ...h6 and ...g5 to push the white bishop away. } ) 
14. bxc3 O-O {[%cal Ge6d5]} 
15.-- ( { Black is ready to play ...Bd5 next with a good position. In an email game White continued with the defensive } 15.Bxc6 bxc6 16.Be3 { , but that was pleasant for Black after } 16...Bd5 { . } )
