A fun fact: when the white bishop is on g5 then ...Be6 is almost always good! If the bishop is not on g5 then ...Be6 often is dubious. } ) 
7. a3 { Probably the best move. If White doesn't know it beforehand, there is no chance they will play this! As we've seen, White has tried a lot of other moves, which you could say are more natural. } g6 ( 7...Qd7 { is also popular, but I prefer to develop the kingside as quickly as possible. Of course there are some issues on d5, but we can handle them! } ) 
8. Bxf6 { A standard reaction. } exf6 
9. Nf3 a6 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { A nice prophylactic move that covers the b5-square. Of course } 9...Bg7 { is also fine, but then White might consider to take twice on d5 and go Qe2+ and Qb5. } ) 
10. Be2 Bg7 
11. O-O O-O 
12. c5 ( 12.b4 f5 { is also good for Black. } ) Re8 $146  ( { So far only } 12...f5 { has been played. That is also good, but } ) ( 12...Re8 { has a nice point. } ) 
13. Qd2 Bf5! 
14. Rfe1 Be4! {[%csl Ge4]} { This is it. The bishop is great in the centre of the board. } 
15. b4 f5 {[%cal Ge4f3,Gh7h6,Gg6g5,Gd8f6,Ga8d8][%csl Gd4]} { Black is better. We can always take on f3 and win the d4-pawn, but be aware that it usually costs us our d5-pawn in return! So we are in no hurry. First we can improve our position on the kingside, for instance with ...h6 and ...g5, and then maybe ...Qf6 and ...Rad8. In the meantime White can only wait for us to play ...Bxf3. } 
