1. e4 c6 
2. c4 { This move is very popular at the club level. White plays a kind of Panov, but without the move d4. It speeds everything up and very soon White gets some extra possibilities. We don't need to fear it. Rather to the contrary: if White tries to get more out of the opening than there is, it may backfire! } d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. cxd5 ( { Here } 4.d4 { would just transpose to the Panov, which we've seen in the previous three chapters. } ) ( 4.Nf3 Nf6 { will also inevitably transpose to other lines. } ) Nf6 ( { We want to take on d5 with the knight. Of course we avoid } 4...Qxd5 5.Nc3 { when White gains a tempo on our queen and gets a good version of the IQP. } ) ( { Now after } 4...Nf6 { the most played move is } 5.Nc3 { , but there are two important alternatives, because White can also give a check, either with the bishop ( } { 5.Bb5+ ) or with the queen ( 5.Qa4+ ), and try to hold on to the d5-pawn, or at least make Black sweat to get it back. I think Black gets excellent chances in both lines, but there are many tricky decisions, so it is worth paying attention to those lines. } ) 
5. Bb5+ Nbd7 ( 5...Bd7 6.Bc4 { is annoying. The bishop on d7 is in the way of our other pieces and makes it harder to win the d5-pawn back. } ) 
6. Nc3 a6! { Immediately attacking the bishop. White will not be allowed to enjoy the extra d5-pawn in a quiet place. } 
7. Qa4 { Pinning the a-pawn is the critical response. } Rb8 {[%cal Ga6b5]} ( { Now the bishop is hanging, so White is forced to make a decision. } 7...g6 { followed by ...Bg7 and ...O-O is a good alternative. } ) 
8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most active, and also the move that provides the best winning chances. You should be ready to sac a pawn for the initiative to play like this, but who isn't? } ( { Safe and sound is } 8...Qxd7 { when } 9.Qxd7+ Bxd7 10.d4 b5 11.a3 { leads to a balanced ending. } ) 
9. Qb3 e6! ( { A nice move. Black is more than ready to give a pawn to blast open the position and dominate the light squares. } 9...b5 { is more quiet, but also fine. } ) 
10. dxe6 Bxe6 {[%cal Ge6b3][%csl Ge1]} { This is really risky for White with the king still in the centre and bad development. } 
11. Qa4+ b5 $146  { Black has fantastic compensation. } 
12. Qxa6 ( 12.Qd1 Bc4 { is also terrible for White. } ) Qc7 {[%cal Ge6c8][%csl Ga6]} { Threatening to trap the queen with ...Bc8. } 
13. Nge2 ( 13.Nxb5? { loses the knight to } 13...Qe5+ { . } ) Bc8 
14. Nxb5 { The only move, but it loses. } Qe5 
15. Qc6+ Bd7 
16. Nc7+ Kd8 {[%csl Rc7,Rc6]} { Black wins a piece and the game. } 
