1. e4 c6 
2. c4 { This move is very popular at the club level. White plays a kind of Panov, but without the move d4. It speeds everything up and very soon White gets some extra possibilities. We don't need to fear it. Rather to the contrary: if White tries to get more out of the opening than there is, it may backfire! } d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. cxd5 ( { Here } 4.d4 { would just transpose to the Panov, which we've seen in the previous three chapters. } ) ( 4.Nf3 Nf6 { will also inevitably transpose to other lines. } ) Nf6 ( { We want to take on d5 with the knight. Of course we avoid } 4...Qxd5 5.Nc3 { when White gains a tempo on our queen and gets a good version of the IQP. } ) ( { Now after } 4...Nf6 { the most played move is } 5.Nc3 { , but there are two important alternatives, because White can also give a check, either with the bishop ( } { 5.Bb5+ ) or with the queen ( 5.Qa4+ ), and try to hold on to the d5-pawn, or at least make Black sweat to get it back. I think Black gets excellent chances in both lines, but there are many tricky decisions, so it is worth paying attention to those lines. } ) 
5. Qa4+ { Another cunning check, forcing us to block on d7, making it harder for us to win the d5-pawn back. } Nbd7 ( { Here too } 5...Bd7 6.Qb3 { would make it hard for Black to regain the pawn. And } ) ( 5...Qd7? 6.Bb5 { should definitely be avoided! } ) 
6. Nc3 a6!? ( { Here Black can flick in ...a6 just to add a touch of originality. In fact there is no reason to deviate, since the mainline } 6...g6 { is also fine: } ) ( 6...g6 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.Bc4 O-O 9.d3 a6 10.Qa3 { has been tested in hundreds of games. The play is complicated, but probably balanced after } 10...b6 11.O-O Bb7 12.Re1 Re8 { when White should try the fashionable } 13.Be3 b5 14.Bb3 { . Here } 14...Nb6 { should equalize. } ) 
7. Nf3 { The clearly most played move. White imitates the mainline. } ( 7.Bb5 Rb8! { would transpose to the line [/variation/41962260/#/7/b] 5.Bb5+. } ) g6 
8. Bc4 { The most played move. White continues according to plan, not thinking that the little move ...a6 makes much of a difference. } Bg7 
9. d3 Rb8! {[%cal Gb7b5]} { We postpone castling. The threat ...b5 causes White some problems. } 
10. Bb3 b5 {[%csl Ga4]} { Where should the queen go? } 
11. Qf4 ( 11.Qb4 a5 { doesn't help White! } ) Bb7 
12. O-O Nc5 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc5b3,Gc5d3][%csl Gd5]} 
13. d6 { Best. The pawn was lost anyway. } Qxd6 
14. Qxd6 exd6 
15. Re1+ { This seems like a very disturbing check since we haven't managed to castle yet. However, we have a cool response. } Kd7! {[%csl Gf7]} { Just leaving the f-pawn en prise. } 
16. Bxf7 Rhf8 
