[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "16) Pseudo-Panov 2.c4"]
[Black "Pseudo-Panov 2.c4 with 5.Nc3 #8"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B10"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42197272"]

1. e4 c6 
2. c4 { This move is very popular at the club level. White plays a kind of Panov, but without the move d4. It speeds everything up and very soon White gets some extra possibilities. We don't need to fear it. Rather to the contrary: if White tries to get more out of the opening than there is, it may backfire! } d5 
3. exd5 cxd5 
4. cxd5 ( { Here } 4.d4 { would just transpose to the Panov, which we've seen in the previous three chapters. } ) ( 4.Nf3 Nf6 { will also inevitably transpose to other lines. } ) Nf6 ( { We want to take on d5 with the knight. Of course we avoid } 4...Qxd5 5.Nc3 { when White gains a tempo on our queen and gets a good version of the IQP. } ) ( { Now after } 4...Nf6 { the most played move is } 5.Nc3 { , but there are two important alternatives, because White can also give a check, either with the bishop ( } { 5.Bb5+ ) or with the queen ( 5.Qa4+ ), and try to hold on to the d5-pawn, or at least make Black sweat to get it back. I think Black gets excellent chances in both lines, but there are many tricky decisions, so it is worth paying attention to those lines. } ) 
5. Nc3 { The most played move, and also the strongest in my opinion. White just develops, pretending to be totally happy about a future with an isolated d-pawn. } Nxd5 
6. Nf3 { This flexible move is key to the whole variation. If White prematurely tries to play actively with their light-squared bishop Black has fewer problems. } ( 6.d4 { would just transpose to a normal Panov. } ) Nc6 ( { Necessary to make the 2.c4 system fit with our Panov repertoire. If you don't mind going outside the bounds of this repertoire, } 6...e6 { is also fine. } ) 
7. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5e8]} { Pinning the knight and sometimes a prelude to taking on c6 and ruin our pawn structure. } ( 7.d4 { would again transpose to a regular Panov. Meanwhile, } ) ( 7.Bc4 { gains a tempo on the d5-knight and transposes to the 6.Bc4 line [/variation/41962306/#/8/b] after } 7...Nb6 8.Bb3 Na5!? { . } ) g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8]} ( { A great fighting move. Black wants to play ...Bg7 and castle, with a kind of Grunfeld. The most played } 7...e6 { is solid and fine as well, but the play is far away from this repertoire where we are used to having our bishop on g7 in so many lines. } ) 
8. Qa4 {[%csl Gc6]} { The critical continuation. White immediately attacks c6. } Qd6 ( { Just protecting c6. It is possible to sacrifice a pawn with } 8...Nb6 { , but the text is simple and good. } ) 
9. Ne4 ( { White is positionally worse and has to do something before Black is fully developed. } 9.O-O Bg7 10.Re1 O-O { is fine for Black. } ) Qe6! ( { Pinning the knight. } 9...Qc7 10.Qd4! { would be an annoying double attack on our knight and rook. } ) 
10. Nfg5 {[%cal Gg5e6]} Qd7 {[%mdl 32768]} 
11. Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d7]} Qc7 { Our queen is pushed around. } 
12. Qd4 {[%cal Gd4h8]} { Each time White moves there is a major threat. Let's hope it will soon stop! } Nf6 
13. Qc4 {[%cal Gc4f7]} e6 
14. Qc3 {[%cal Gc3f6]} ( 14.O-O Be7 { and White's initiative evaporates. } ) Bg7 
15. Nce4 {[%cal Gc3g7][%csl Gf6]} e5 { White still has a few bullets left. } 
16. Bxc6+ bxc6 
17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 
18. Ne4 Be7 ( { If } 18...Bg7 { then } 19.Qa3 { is annoying. } ) 
19. O-O O-O 
20.-- ( { Finally we are safe. The position is balanced. A sample line is } 20.d4 Bf5 21.Ng3 exd4 22.Qxd4 Rfd8 23.Qe3 Be6 { and Black is in good shape with the bishop pair. } )
*

