[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Schandorff's Caro-Kann"]
[White "17) Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "Two Knights: 5.Ng3"]
[Date "2024.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B10"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41962342"]

1. e4 c6 
2. Nf3 d5 
3. Nc3 { The Two-knights variation is one of the most popular - and best! - anti Caro-Kann lines. Of course, White could also start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@ 2.Nc3 d5 and then play 3.Nf3 , that doesn't matter. What is important is that the idea of the whole line is to make Black refrain from the typical Caro-move ...dxe4, because Black can't get what they normally want. That is generally true, but not in our case! }dxe4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Since we play the ...Nf6-line against the Classical Caro-Kann we can play like that here as well, so I take the liberty of skipping the mainline 3...Bg4 entirely. I will just add one comment: 3...Bg4 is a positionally fine move. Often Black has to take on f3, but that is not bad, because the pawn structure on the light squares is very solid and Black's dark-squared bishop will be strong. But White gets the pair of bishops... } 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black plays like in the Classical. If White takes on f6 the similarity is striking, so usually White looks for alternative ways of playing. } 
5. Ng3 c5!? {[%cal Gb8c6]} { We lose a tempo with the c-pawn, but White has also lost a lot of time with the knight! Black prepares ...Nc6 with a nice position. } ( { Instead, } 5...h5 { is the most popular move. } ) 
6. Bc4 ( 6.d4 Nc6 { is also fine for Black. } ) Nc6 
7. O-O e6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8][%csl Gd4]} { Black has control over the important d4-square and calmly finishes development. } 
8. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} { White tries to activate the final pieces. } Be7 
9. Bb2 O-O 
10. Re1 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { Next is ...Bb7 with a very harmonious position. } 
*

