1. e4 c6 
2. Nf3 d5 
3. Nc3 { The Two-knights variation is one of the most popular - and best! - anti Caro-Kann lines. Of course, White could also start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@ 2.Nc3 d5 and then play 3.Nf3 , that doesn't matter. What is important is that the idea of the whole line is to make Black refrain from the typical Caro-move ...dxe4, because Black can't get what they normally want. That is generally true, but not in our case! }dxe4 { Since we play the ...Nf6-line against the Classical Caro-Kann we can play like that here as well, so I take the liberty of skipping the mainline 3...Bg4 entirely. I will just add one comment: 3...Bg4 is a positionally fine move. Often Black has to take on f3, but that is not bad, because the pawn structure on the light squares is very solid and Black's dark-squared bishop will be strong. But White gets the pair of bishops... } 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black plays like in the Classical. If White takes on f6 the similarity is striking, so usually White looks for alternative ways of playing. } 
5. Qe2 Nxe4 ( { This fancy move is the modern mainline of the Two Knights. White protects the e4-knight and is ready to take on f6 when Black is forced to recapture with the g-pawn, which is something we would go far to avoid. At the same time White sets a nasty trap, because Black's most obvious move loses instantly: } 5...Nbd7? 6.Nd6 { mate! } ) 
6. Qxe4 { Quite an unsual position that demands unusual solutions. } Be6! ( { Perhaps it looks strange to block the e-pawn, but in fact the intention is to play ...Bd5 next and maybe even take on f3. It is a very original solution. Black has two other good moves, } 6...Qa5 { and } ) ( 6...Nd7 { , which I have covered in Playing the Caro-Kann, but these days I go with } ) ( 6...Be6! ) 
7. b3! {[%cal Gc1b2]} { The best reply. White intends to develop the dark-squared bishop to the excellent b2-square. } Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6]} ( { The knight joins the battle. } 7...Bd5 { is also possible. } ) 
8. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2g7]} ( { The bishop is strong here with a nice long diagonal. } 8.Bc4 { is met with the smart } 8...Nf6 9.Qe2 Bd5! { and Black is fine. } ) Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} { Hitting the queen. It is unclear where it should go. } 
9. Qf4 { Preventing ...Bf5. Now Black has to develop in a completely different way. } g6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
10. Bc4 ( 10.O-O-O Bg7 11.h4 Qd6= { is given by Banzea. } ) Bxc4 $146  
11. Qxc4 Bg7 { Black has solved all development problems. } 
12. O-O O-O 
13. Rfe1 Re8 {[%csl Gd5]} { The position is balanced. Often Black can use the d5-square at some point, either with the queen or with the knight. } 
