8. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2g7]} ( { The bishop is strong here with a nice long diagonal. } 8.Bc4 { is met with the smart } 8...Nf6 9.Qe2 Bd5! { and Black is fine. } ) Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} { Hitting the queen. It is unclear where it should go. } 
9. Qe3 { Maybe the best. } Nd5! {[%cal Gd5e3]} { We continue to bother the white queen. This is recommended by Banzea and I'll go with his suggestion! The only problem is that this move is an invitation to repeat moves. Theoretically that is no problem of course. After all, we're playing as Black. For the practical player there can be some mixed feelings about the whole affair, so I offer two ways to deviate even at this advanced point: } ( { A: } 9...Bf5 10.Nd4! Bg6 11.f4 { gives White some initiative, although the position is far from clear after } 11...Qa5 { . } ) ( { B: } 9...Qa5!? { has done well, though objectively White is probably slightly better. } ) 
10. Qd4 ( { The critical continuation. } 10.Qe4 Nf6 11.Qe3 Nd5 { is the aforementioned repetition. Meanwhile, } ) ( 10.Qe5 Qc7 { is fine for Black, who seldom has any problems in this line when the queens come off. } ) Nf6 $146  ( 10...Bf5 { is a good alternative, for instance } 11.Bd3 Bxd3 12.Qxd3 e6 13.O-O Nf6 14.Qe2 Bd6 { with a normal Caro-Kann position that is balanced. } ) 
11. O-O-O { Most queen moves would transpose to the other lines. } Bg4! { Black solves the problem with the bishop and is fine. } 
12. Qe3 Qa5!? {[%csl Ga2]} ( 12...Nd5 { is also fine. } ) 
13. a4 e6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
14. h3 { It is nice for White to clarify the situation. } Bxf3 
15. Qxf3 {[%cal Gb2f6,Gf3f6]} O-O-O! { It is not necessary to protect the f6-knight with ...Be7. Now Black is fine after a quiet continuation, so the critical test must be if White takes the bait. } 
16. Bxf6 gxf6 
17. Qxf6 Bd6! {[%cal Gh8f8,Gd6e5][%csl Gc1]} { Black has good play on the dark squares and full compensation for the pawn. } 
18. Qxf7? ( { Greed is severely punished. } 18.Be2 Rhf8 { would still be roughly equal. } ) Qe5! {[%cal Gd8f8,Ge5a1][%csl Rc1,Rf7]} 
19.-- ( { Black wins as given by Banzea. Mate in one is threatened and ...Rdf8 next will trap the white queen. A sample line is } 19.d4 Ba3+! 20.Kb1 Rxd4 21.Rxd4 Qxd4 22.Qxe6+ Kb8 23.c3 Qxc3 24.Qe2 Rd8 { and it is curtains. } )
