3. d3 { This innocent looking move has been trendy the last couple of years, which is actually quite surprising because it looks like Black can just take on e4 and exchange queens and have no problems whatsoever. However, practice has shown that the ending is not as simple as it seems at first sight, and White has a clear plus score. } { Only if you dig a little deeper does the truth start to appear. The line is typical of the modern approach to opening theory: White is not striving for a real advantage, but rather they seek a positional game with full control and a slight pull, even if it is very tiny, so they can keep the game going and hope to get an edge later on. It is similar to a popular line in the Queen's Gambit Accepted: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 e6 5.Bxc4 c5 6.O-O a6 7.dxc5 and the queens come off. White never loses, and occasionally they win a game and are happy. Theoretically Black is fine, but in practice it can be a little annoying. It is almost like you're not allowed to get a real game! } { Back to the Caro. After 3.d3 Black can try moves like 3...g6 or 3...Qc7 to avoid the queen exchange, but come on! I find it hard to believe that taking on e4 is not the best move. It is logical and it is simple, so it must be good! } dxe4 
4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 
5. Kxd1 Nf6 {[%csl Ge4]} { Hitting e4. Our knight comes out with tempo. Now White has several ways to defend the pawn. } 
6. Nbd2 g6 {[%mdl 32768]} { I like to fianchetto the bishop. It will be great on g7. But there is even a more ambitious idea: to play ...Bh6 and exchange the bishops. } 
7. Ne1 { This is similar to 7.Ne5. } Bh6! { A nice move. We will welcome the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, which will diminish the potential pressure White can create. } 
8. f3 Be6 
9. Nd3 Nbd7 { Black has no problems. As soon as White moves the d2-knight we exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 
