1. e4 c6 
2. d3 ( { Of course, theoretically speaking this continuation is nothing to worry about. For the practical player } 2.d3 { is very relevant, however, because quite often your opponent is not interested in a theoretical discussion and just wants to get a playable position. The idea behind } ) ( 2.d3 { is to go for a King's Indian set-up with g3, Bg2 and so on. } ) d5 {[%mdl 32768]} 
3. Nc3 d4! ( { Already going for the advantage! The safe } 3...dxe4 { leads to an equal endgame one way or another: } 4.dxe4 Qxd1+ 5.Kxd1 e5 { , or } 4.Nxe4 Nf6 5.Nf3 { 5.Nxf6+ exf6 is fine. We know this structure! } 5...Nxe4 6.dxe4 Qxd1+ 7.Kxd1 Nd7 8.Be3 e5 9.Bc4 f6 10.Ke2 Bc5= { . } ) 
4. Nce2 e5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]} { I am a 1.d4 player, so I know this structure very well with colours reversed, and I really appreciate the extra space. } 
5. g3 Bd6 
6. Bg2 c5! {[%cal Gb8c6]} { Making room for ...Nc6. } 
7. f4 Nc6 
8. Nf3 Nge7 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc8e6,Gd8d7,Ge8c8]} { This is a typical King's Indian reversed. Black is very flexible. I would probably go for a setup with ...f6, ...Be6, ...Qd7 and maybe ...O-O-O, known from the Saemisch variation of the King's Indian. } 
*

