3. f3 { The Fantasy variation. This is a very popular way to meet the Caro-Kann at club level, but it occasionally pops up in all kind of tournaments. For instance, I have faced it against a strong grandmaster in the European Team Championship.

White just defends the e4-pawn and is ready to recapture with the f-pawn, so there is no chance Black will be able to get the bishop out to f5. The Fantasy can lead to very tricky play within a few moves, so you better be prepared! } e6 { Solid and sound. Now it is a kind of French with a white pawn on f3, which is very unusual and something we can hope to exploit. OK, our pawn is on c6 too, but that is not really a drawback, it's merely a loss of time once we get the typical break ...c5 in. } ( { In my previous work I have recommended the sharp and very direct } 3...dxe4 4.fxe4 e5 { , but now I am not so sure, because the arising complications can be quite hard to handle. I am talking about } 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.c3 Nd7 7.Bd3 Ngf6 8.O-O Bd6 { with an interesting position that probably is balanced, but is definitely easier to play as White, who often gets the initiative. Long story short: It is a tough line to master and White scores really well. Let's try something completely different! } ) 
4. Nc3 { The most natural move. } Nd7 ( { A cool move. Black stays flexible. The main move is the French-like } 4...Bb4 { , but } ) ( 4...Nd7 { is much harder for White to meet. Depending on what White does we can still play ...Bb4, but often a quick ...Qb6 will be very strong. Also, 4...Nd7 prepares the typical positional strike ...dxe4 followed by ...e5. } ) 
5. Be3 { The natural square for the bishop. } Bb4 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8][%csl Gb4]} { A good active square for the bishop. It is important to get it out so we can continue with ...Ne7 and ...O-O. } 
6. Bd3 Ne7 {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. Nge2 { Both sides develop very naturally, but now Black has an important decision to make. } dxe4! { Good timing. } 
8. fxe4 e5 { This shows the positional idea of 7...dxe4. Black will get good play on the dark squares. } 
9. O-O ( 9.d5? cxd5 { just wins the d5-pawn because of the pin. } ) exd4 
10. Bxd4 ( 10.Nxd4 O-O { is also pleasant for Black, with a nice square on e5 for the knight. } ) O-O 
11. Kh1 Bc5 {[%csl Ge5]} { Black is just better after the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. One of the knights will be very strong on e5 and White's remaining bishop is pretty bad. In the long run the e4-pawn will also be a significant weakness. } 
