5. Nxf3 Nf6 { I covered this position in my recent Queen's Gambit Declined course. It is the so-called Blackmar-Diemer Gambit that usually comes after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.e4 dxe4 4.f3 exf3 5.Nxf3 and now 5...c6! is the best, which leads us straight to the Caro-Kann! The gambit is more or less refuted, so here I will just give the same convincing antidote. } 
6. Bc4 ( 6.Bd3 Bg4 { is just good for Black. } ) Bf5 ( { A little care is needed. } 6...Bg4? { runs into } 7.Bxf7+! Kxf7 8.Ne5+ { . } ) 
7. Ne5 e6 
8. g4 { This very direct attempt looks scary, but Black has a surprising antidote. } Nfd7! {[%cal Gd8h4]} { This opens a path for the queen to give a higly disturbing check on h4. Tactically it is justified because the c4-bishop is loose in many lines. } 
9. gxf5 Nxe5 
10. Be2 ( 10.dxe5 Qh4+ { followed by ...Qxc4 is the point. } ) Qh4+ 
11. Kf1 Qh3+ 
12. Ke1 Be7! {[%cal Ge7h4]} { The bishop joins the attack. } 
13. dxe5 ( { Taking the bait. Objectively } 13.Bf4 { is better, but after the simple } 13...Ned7 14.fxe6 Qxe6 { Black is a pawn up and White can't castle. } ) Qg2! {[%cal Gg2h1]} 
14. Rf1 Bh4+ 
15. Kd2 Na6 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 
16.-- ( { Black prepares long castling with check. The white king can't escape. Here I stopped the analysis in my QGD course, but let's add a few moves just for fun: } 16.Ke3 Bg5+ 17.Rf4 Bxf4+ 18.Kxf4 Qf2+ 19.Bf3 Rd8 20.Qe2 Qh4+ 21.Ke3 { or 21.Bg4 Rd4+ 22.Ne4 Nc5 } 21...Qd4 { . } )
